(globalThis.TURBOPACK||(globalThis.TURBOPACK=[])).push(["object"==typeof document?document.currentScript:void 0,57249,(e,i,a)=>{i.exports=JSON.parse('[{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-lln","question":"An actuary can estimate with surprising accuracy how many of 100,000 insured drivers will become disabled this year, even though she cannot say which ones. Which principle makes this possible?","options":["The law of large numbers","The principle of indemnity","The rule of adhesion","The doctrine of utmost good faith"],"answer":"The law of large numbers","topic":"Law of Large Numbers","explanation":"The law of large numbers says predictions get more accurate as the number of similar exposure units grows. It\'s what lets insurers price premiums reliably — they can\'t predict WHO will suffer a loss, only HOW MANY will."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-lln","question":"Premiums can be calculated reliably because predictions of loss become more accurate as the number of similar exposure units grows. This concept is called:","options":["The law of large numbers","Adverse selection","Experience rating","The law of averages"],"answer":"The law of large numbers","topic":"Law of Large Numbers","explanation":"The law of large numbers says predictions get more accurate as the number of similar exposure units grows. It\'s what lets insurers price premiums reliably — they can\'t predict WHO will suffer a loss, only HOW MANY will."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-hazard","question":"A warehouse owner stores oily rags in a pile next to the furnace. The rags are an example of:","options":["A physical hazard","A peril","A moral hazard","A morale hazard"],"answer":"A physical hazard","topic":"Hazards","explanation":"A hazard increases the chance or severity of loss. Physical = tangible conditions (oily rags, ice). Moral = dishonesty (fraud, exaggerated claims). Morale = carelessness because insurance exists (unlocked doors)."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-hazard","question":"Trent exaggerates the value of the items stolen from his car when he files his claim. Trent\'s dishonesty is an example of:","options":["A moral hazard","A morale hazard","A physical hazard","A peril"],"answer":"A moral hazard","topic":"Hazards","explanation":"A hazard increases the chance or severity of loss. Physical = tangible conditions (oily rags, ice). Moral = dishonesty (fraud, exaggerated claims). Morale = carelessness because insurance exists (unlocked doors)."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-hazard","question":"Since buying renters insurance, Dana has stopped locking her apartment door, figuring \\"the insurance will cover it.\\" Her new carelessness is an example of:","options":["A morale hazard","A moral hazard","A physical hazard","A speculative risk"],"answer":"A morale hazard","topic":"Hazards","explanation":"A hazard increases the chance or severity of loss. Physical = tangible conditions (oily rags, ice). Moral = dishonesty (fraud, exaggerated claims). Morale = carelessness because insurance exists (unlocked doors)."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-purespec","question":"Devon bets $500 on a playoff game, where he may win or lose. Priya owns a home that faces only the chance of loss from fire. Which statement is TRUE?","options":["Priya\'s exposure is a pure risk and is insurable; Devon\'s is speculative and is not","Both exposures are insurable pure risks","Devon\'s exposure is insurable because the outcome is measurable","Neither exposure is insurable"],"answer":"Priya\'s exposure is a pure risk and is insurable; Devon\'s is speculative and is not","topic":"Pure vs. Speculative Risk","explanation":"Pure risk has only the chance of loss or no loss — it\'s insurable. Speculative risk includes a chance of GAIN (gambling, investing) — never insurable."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-purespec","question":"Which statement concerning pure and speculative risk is TRUE?","options":["Only pure risks are insurable","Only speculative risks are insurable","Both pure and speculative risks are insurable","Speculative risks involve no chance of gain"],"answer":"Only pure risks are insurable","topic":"Pure vs. Speculative Risk","explanation":"Pure risk has only the chance of loss or no loss — it\'s insurable. Speculative risk includes a chance of GAIN (gambling, investing) — never insurable."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-riskdef","question":"As insurers use the term, \\"risk\\" is best defined as:","options":["Uncertainty regarding financial loss","The certainty that a loss will occur","Any dangerous activity","The dollar amount of a claim"],"answer":"Uncertainty regarding financial loss","topic":"Definition of Risk","explanation":"In insurance, risk means uncertainty regarding financial loss — not danger, not the loss amount, just the uncertainty of whether a loss will occur."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-riskdef","question":"Every exposure an insurer is willing to cover shares one essential element. What is it?","options":["Uncertainty about whether a financial loss will occur","A guaranteed payout amount","Government backing","A chance of profit for the insured"],"answer":"Uncertainty about whether a financial loss will occur","topic":"Definition of Risk","explanation":"In insurance, risk means uncertainty regarding financial loss — not danger, not the loss amount, just the uncertainty of whether a loss will occur."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-peril","question":"A tornado that levels a barn is an example of:","options":["A peril","A hazard","A risk retention","A speculative risk"],"answer":"A peril","topic":"Peril vs. Hazard","explanation":"A peril is the CAUSE of loss (fire, flood, tornado, death). A hazard is a CONDITION that increases the chance of loss. Conditions of the body (like poor eyesight) are not perils."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-peril","question":"Which of the following is the CAUSE of a loss, rather than a condition that increases the chance of one?","options":["A flood","Unsalted icy steps","Smoking in bed","Poor building maintenance"],"answer":"A flood","topic":"Peril vs. Hazard","explanation":"A peril is the CAUSE of loss (fire, flood, tornado, death). A hazard is a CONDITION that increases the chance of loss. Conditions of the body (like poor eyesight) are not perils."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-peril","question":"All of the following are perils EXCEPT:","options":["Nearsightedness","Fire","Windstorm","Theft"],"answer":"Nearsightedness","topic":"Peril vs. Hazard","explanation":"A peril is the CAUSE of loss (fire, flood, tornado, death). A hazard is a CONDITION that increases the chance of loss. Conditions of the body (like poor eyesight) are not perils."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-methods","question":"Rosa refuses to ever ride a motorcycle because she fears being injured. Rosa is handling risk through:","options":["Avoidance","Reduction","Retention","Transference"],"answer":"Avoidance","topic":"Risk-Handling Methods (ARRT)","explanation":"Four ways to handle risk: Avoid (eliminate the exposure), Reduce (lower likelihood/severity — sprinklers, alarms), Retain (accept it yourself — self-insure), Transfer (shift it to another party — buying insurance)."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-methods","question":"A restaurant installs a kitchen sprinkler system to limit fire damage. This is risk:","options":["Reduction","Avoidance","Retention","Transference"],"answer":"Reduction","topic":"Risk-Handling Methods (ARRT)","explanation":"Four ways to handle risk: Avoid (eliminate the exposure), Reduce (lower likelihood/severity — sprinklers, alarms), Retain (accept it yourself — self-insure), Transfer (shift it to another party — buying insurance)."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-methods","question":"A courier company with 300 vans pays collision losses out of its own reserve fund rather than buying coverage. This is risk:","options":["Retention","Reduction","Transference","Avoidance"],"answer":"Retention","topic":"Risk-Handling Methods (ARRT)","explanation":"Four ways to handle risk: Avoid (eliminate the exposure), Reduce (lower likelihood/severity — sprinklers, alarms), Retain (accept it yourself — self-insure), Transfer (shift it to another party — buying insurance)."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-methods","question":"Marcus buys a homeowners policy, shifting the financial consequences of a fire to an insurer. This is risk:","options":["Transference","Retention","Avoidance","Reduction"],"answer":"Transference","topic":"Risk-Handling Methods (ARRT)","explanation":"Four ways to handle risk: Avoid (eliminate the exposure), Reduce (lower likelihood/severity — sprinklers, alarms), Retain (accept it yourself — self-insure), Transfer (shift it to another party — buying insurance)."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-elements","question":"Which of the following describe elements of an insurable risk? I - The loss must be due to chance. II - The loss must be definite and measurable. III - The loss must not be catastrophic. IV - There must be a large number of similar exposure units.","options":["I, II, III, and IV","I and II only","II, III, and IV only","I, II, and III only"],"answer":"I, II, III, and IV","topic":"Elements of Insurable Risk","explanation":"An insurable risk must be: due to chance, definite and measurable, statistically predictable, NOT catastrophic, part of a large group of similar exposures, and randomly selected."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-elements","question":"An insurer declines to write a policy covering losses from a single mega-earthquake striking an entire metro area. Which element of insurable risk is missing?","options":["The loss must not be catastrophic","The loss must be due to chance","The loss must be definite and measurable","There must be a large number of exposure units"],"answer":"The loss must not be catastrophic","topic":"Elements of Insurable Risk","explanation":"An insurable risk must be: due to chance, definite and measurable, statistically predictable, NOT catastrophic, part of a large group of similar exposures, and randomly selected."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-adverse","question":"A disproportionate share of applicants for a new critical-illness policy turn out to already have troubling symptoms. This tendency is called:","options":["Adverse selection","Moral hazard","The law of large numbers","Subrogation"],"answer":"Adverse selection","topic":"Adverse Selection","explanation":"Adverse selection is the tendency of people in poor health (higher risk) to seek insurance more than low-risk people. Insurers control it through underwriting."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-adverse","question":"Adverse selection is the tendency of people in ______ to seek insurance to a greater extent than other risks.","options":["Poor health","High income brackets","Rural areas","Low-risk occupations"],"answer":"Poor health","topic":"Adverse Selection","explanation":"Adverse selection is the tendency of people in poor health (higher risk) to seek insurance more than low-risk people. Insurers control it through underwriting."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-hlv","question":"The concept that measures a person\'s worth by the future earnings they would generate for their family is called:","options":["Human life value","Net worth analysis","Adverse selection","The indemnity principle"],"answer":"Human life value","topic":"Human Life Value","explanation":"Human life value measures a person\'s worth by their future earning potential — the essence of a family\'s economic existence. It\'s the economic root of life and health insurance."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-hlv","question":"The purpose and function of insurance has its roots in economics and ______.","options":["Human life value","Government mandates","Stock market returns","Actuarial science"],"answer":"Human life value","topic":"Human Life Value","explanation":"Human life value measures a person\'s worth by their future earning potential — the essence of a family\'s economic existence. It\'s the economic root of life and health insurance."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-hlv","question":"Human life value is, at its core, a measure of an individual\'s or family\'s ______.","options":["Economic existence","Social standing","Physical health","Insurance history"],"answer":"Economic existence","topic":"Human Life Value","explanation":"Human life value measures a person\'s worth by their future earning potential — the essence of a family\'s economic existence. It\'s the economic root of life and health insurance."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-function","question":"Which statement best describes the core function of insurance?","options":["It minimizes the individual\'s loss by spreading financial risk across a large group","It guarantees that no one ever suffers a financial loss","It generates investment profits for policyholders","It eliminates the underlying causes of loss"],"answer":"It minimizes the individual\'s loss by spreading financial risk across a large group","topic":"Function of Insurance","explanation":"Insurance minimizes individual loss by spreading financial risk across a large group. Life and health insurance specifically address the economic losses of death, sickness, and accidents."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-function","question":"Life and health insurance developed primarily as a practical answer to the economic losses associated with:","options":["Death, sickness, and accidents","Inflation, taxes, and unemployment","Crime, fraud, and theft","War, famine, and drought"],"answer":"Death, sickness, and accidents","topic":"Function of Insurance","explanation":"Insurance minimizes individual loss by spreading financial risk across a large group. Life and health insurance specifically address the economic losses of death, sickness, and accidents."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-transfer","question":"People buy insurance mainly because it is one of the most effective ways of:","options":["Transferring risk","Avoiding risk entirely","Increasing personal wealth","Eliminating perils"],"answer":"Transferring risk","topic":"Insurance as Risk Transfer","explanation":"Buying insurance is the classic example of risk TRANSFERENCE — the insurer assumes financial risk in exchange for premium. Of the four ARRT methods, transference is the basis of insurance."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-transfer","question":"Of the four risk-handling techniques, the one that forms the basis of insurance is:","options":["Transference","Avoidance","Reduction","Retention"],"answer":"Transference","topic":"Insurance as Risk Transfer","explanation":"Buying insurance is the classic example of risk TRANSFERENCE — the insurer assumes financial risk in exchange for premium. Of the four ARRT methods, transference is the basis of insurance."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-uninsurable","question":"Vince wants a policy that pays him if his cryptocurrency holdings lose value. Why will insurers refuse?","options":["Investment losses are speculative risks, which are uninsurable","The potential loss is too small to measure","Cryptocurrency is regulated federally, not by states","Vince lacks insurable interest in his own assets"],"answer":"Investment losses are speculative risks, which are uninsurable","topic":"Uninsurable Risks","explanation":"Speculative risks (investments, gambling) and catastrophic exposures (region-wide tsunami, war) fail the elements of insurable risk and will be declined."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 1","group":"d1m1-uninsurable","question":"Which exposure would an insurer most likely refuse to cover?","options":["Region-wide destruction from a tsunami","A homeowner\'s risk of kitchen fire","A delivery driver\'s risk of collision","An office worker\'s risk of disability"],"answer":"Region-wide destruction from a tsunami","topic":"Uninsurable Risks","explanation":"Speculative risks (investments, gambling) and catastrophic exposures (region-wide tsunami, war) fail the elements of insurable risk and will be declined."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-naic","question":"Which statement about the National Association of Insurance Commissioners (NAIC) is NOT correct?","options":["The NAIC has the authority to prosecute and punish criminal violators in the insurance industry","The NAIC is composed of state insurance regulators","The NAIC develops model laws for states to consider adopting","The NAIC works to encourage uniformity among state insurance regulations"],"answer":"The NAIC has the authority to prosecute and punish criminal violators in the insurance industry","topic":"The NAIC","explanation":"The NAIC is an association of state insurance commissioners that promotes uniformity through model laws. It has NO enforcement or prosecution authority — that power belongs to the states."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-naic","question":"The NAIC\'s primary purpose is to:","options":["Encourage uniformity in state insurance regulation through model legislation","Issue insurance licenses in every state","Prosecute insurance fraud at the federal level","Set nationwide premium rates"],"answer":"Encourage uniformity in state insurance regulation through model legislation","topic":"The NAIC","explanation":"The NAIC is an association of state insurance commissioners that promotes uniformity through model laws. It has NO enforcement or prosecution authority — that power belongs to the states."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-agentbroker","question":"In an insurance transaction, a licensed agent legally represents:","options":["The insurer","The applicant and insured","The state Office of Insurance Regulation","Whoever pays the higher fee"],"answer":"The insurer","topic":"Agent vs. Broker","explanation":"An agent legally represents the INSURER. A broker legally represents the APPLICANT/INSURED and shops the market on their behalf."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-agentbroker","question":"In Florida, a broker in an insurance transaction legally represents:","options":["The applicant and insured","The insurer","The Department of Financial Services","The reinsurer"],"answer":"The applicant and insured","topic":"Agent vs. Broker","explanation":"An agent legally represents the INSURER. A broker legally represents the APPLICANT/INSURED and shops the market on their behalf."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-agentbroker","question":"Lena shops the market on behalf of her clients and submits each application to whichever insurer fits best. In these transactions Lena is acting as a:","options":["Broker, representing the applicant","Agent, representing the insurer","Adjuster, representing the insurer","Consultant, representing the state"],"answer":"Broker, representing the applicant","topic":"Agent vs. Broker","explanation":"An agent legally represents the INSURER. A broker legally represents the APPLICANT/INSURED and shops the market on their behalf."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-companies","question":"From Florida\'s perspective, an insurer formed under the laws of Ontario, Canada and licensed to sell in Florida is:","options":["An alien company","A foreign company","A domestic company","An unauthorized company"],"answer":"An alien company","topic":"Domestic / Foreign / Alien","explanation":"Classification is from the viewpoint of the state: incorporated in that state = domestic; another U.S. state = foreign; another country = alien."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-companies","question":"An insurer incorporated in Georgia with offices in Tennessee and licensed to sell insurance in Florida is, from Florida\'s viewpoint, a ______ company.","options":["Foreign","Domestic","Alien","Surplus"],"answer":"Foreign","topic":"Domestic / Foreign / Alien","explanation":"Classification is from the viewpoint of the state: incorporated in that state = domestic; another U.S. state = foreign; another country = alien."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-companies","question":"An insurer incorporated in Florida and selling policies in Florida is classified there as a ______ company.","options":["Domestic","Foreign","Alien","Reciprocal"],"answer":"Domestic","topic":"Domestic / Foreign / Alien","explanation":"Classification is from the viewpoint of the state: incorporated in that state = domestic; another U.S. state = foreign; another country = alien."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-reinsurer","question":"After issuing several jumbo commercial policies, Coastal Life arranges for another company to assume part of the risk. The company accepting that risk is a:","options":["Reinsurer","Risk retention group","Third-party administrator","Service provider"],"answer":"Reinsurer","topic":"Reinsurers","explanation":"A reinsurer accepts portions of risk from other insurance companies. Its customers are insurers, not the public — that\'s why it\'s a specialized branch of the industry."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-reinsurer","question":"Reinsurers are considered a specialized branch of the industry because the customers they insure are:","options":["Insurance companies","Individual policyholders","Government agencies","Independent agents"],"answer":"Insurance companies","topic":"Reinsurers","explanation":"A reinsurer accepts portions of risk from other insurance companies. Its customers are insurers, not the public — that\'s why it\'s a specialized branch of the industry."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-regscope","question":"State regulation of the insurance industry does NOT include:","options":["Making insurance laws","Licensing producers","Reviewing policy forms","Examining insurer finances"],"answer":"Making insurance laws","topic":"Scope of State Regulation","explanation":"Regulators license producers, approve forms, and examine insurers — but they don\'t MAKE laws. Insurance statutes are enacted by the state legislature."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-regscope","question":"Which body actually enacts a state\'s insurance statutes?","options":["The state legislature","The insurance commissioner","The NAIC","The State Guaranty Association"],"answer":"The state legislature","topic":"Scope of State Regulation","explanation":"Regulators license producers, approve forms, and examine insurers — but they don\'t MAKE laws. Insurance statutes are enacted by the state legislature."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-buyersguide","question":"Which of the following is NOT a goal of the Buyer\'s Guide?","options":["Ensuring that buyers obtain the lowest price for insurance","Helping buyers understand basic policy types","Helping buyers compare policies","Helping buyers make informed decisions"],"answer":"Ensuring that buyers obtain the lowest price for insurance","topic":"Buyer\'s Guide","explanation":"The Buyer\'s Guide helps applicants understand and compare policies to make informed decisions. It does NOT guarantee the lowest price."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-buyersguide","question":"The Buyer\'s Guide exists primarily to:","options":["Help applicants understand and compare policies before purchasing","Guarantee the lowest available premium","Replace the policy summary","Advertise an insurer\'s strongest products"],"answer":"Help applicants understand and compare policies before purchasing","topic":"Buyer\'s Guide","explanation":"The Buyer\'s Guide helps applicants understand and compare policies to make informed decisions. It does NOT guarantee the lowest price."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-guaranty","question":"An insurer becomes insolvent while owing claim payments. Which entity steps in so covered claims are still paid?","options":["The State Guaranty Association","The NAIC","The Federal Reserve","The reinsurer of last resort"],"answer":"The State Guaranty Association","topic":"State Guaranty Association","explanation":"If an insurer becomes insolvent, the State Guaranty Association pays covered claims, within limits. It protects policyholders, not insurers."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-guaranty","question":"The State Guaranty Association guarantees that:","options":["Claims will be paid, within limits, if a member insurer becomes insolvent","Premiums will never increase","Every applicant will be approved for coverage","Agents will receive their commissions"],"answer":"Claims will be paid, within limits, if a member insurer becomes insolvent","topic":"State Guaranty Association","explanation":"If an insurer becomes insolvent, the State Guaranty Association pays covered claims, within limits. It protects policyholders, not insurers."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-distribution","question":"Which marketing system does NOT involve the sale of insurance through agents or brokers?","options":["The direct selling system","The independent agency system","The career agency system","The brokerage system"],"answer":"The direct selling system","topic":"Distribution Systems","explanation":"Agency, brokerage, and career systems all use producers. The direct selling (direct response) system sells by mail, phone, and internet with NO agents or brokers."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-distribution","question":"An insurer that markets policies exclusively by mail, phone, and internet — with no producers involved — uses the ______ system.","options":["Direct selling","Independent agency","Managing general agent","Career agency"],"answer":"Direct selling","topic":"Distribution Systems","explanation":"Agency, brokerage, and career systems all use producers. The direct selling (direct response) system sells by mail, phone, and internet with NO agents or brokers."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-advertising","question":"Rules pertaining to testimonials, statistics, and special offers in insurance marketing are found in:","options":["The Advertising Code","The Buyer\'s Guide","The policy summary","The entire contract provision"],"answer":"The Advertising Code","topic":"Advertising Code","explanation":"Rules governing testimonials, statistics, and special offers in insurance marketing live in the Advertising Code."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-advertising","question":"An insurer\'s TV spot features a celebrity endorsement and claims it is \\"rated #1 in claim payments.\\" Which set of rules governs these statements?","options":["The Advertising Code","The parole evidence rule","The free look provision","The USA Patriot Act"],"answer":"The Advertising Code","topic":"Advertising Code","explanation":"Rules governing testimonials, statistics, and special offers in insurance marketing live in the Advertising Code."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-rrg","question":"A group of pharmacists forms its own entity to insure the malpractice liability of its members. This entity is:","options":["A risk retention group","A reinsurer","A multiple employer trust","A service provider"],"answer":"A risk retention group","topic":"Risk Retention Groups","explanation":"An RRG is formed by similar businesses or professionals (e.g., pharmacists) to insure their own liability risks as a group."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-rrg","question":"Which statement about a risk retention group (RRG) is TRUE?","options":["It is formed by similar businesses or professionals to insure their own liability risks","It may insure any member of the general public","It is a federal agency that insures high-risk drivers","It only sells life insurance"],"answer":"It is formed by similar businesses or professionals to insure their own liability risks","topic":"Risk Retention Groups","explanation":"An RRG is formed by similar businesses or professionals (e.g., pharmacists) to insure their own liability risks as a group."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-license","question":"An agent\'s license will terminate if the agent allows how many years to pass without an appointment?","options":["Four","Two","Five","Seven"],"answer":"Four","topic":"License Termination","explanation":"A license terminates after FOUR years without an appointment. Count from the last appointment\'s end."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-license","question":"Glen\'s last appointment ended in 2020 and he never obtained another. What happens to his license in 2024?","options":["It terminates, because four years passed without an appointment","Nothing — licenses never expire","It converts to a temporary license","It is automatically renewed for two more years"],"answer":"It terminates, because four years passed without an appointment","topic":"License Termination","explanation":"A license terminates after FOUR years without an appointment. Count from the last appointment\'s end."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-patriot","question":"The USA Patriot Act was created in response to:","options":["The September 11th attacks","The 2008 financial crisis","Hurricane Andrew","The savings and loan scandal"],"answer":"The September 11th attacks","topic":"USA Patriot Act","explanation":"Passed in response to the September 11th attacks; imposes anti-money-laundering obligations that reach insurers."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-patriot","question":"Which federal law, passed after the September 11th attacks, imposes anti-money-laundering obligations that affect insurers?","options":["The USA Patriot Act","The McCarran-Ferguson Act","HIPAA","The Affordable Care Act"],"answer":"The USA Patriot Act","topic":"USA Patriot Act","explanation":"Passed in response to the September 11th attacks; imposes anti-money-laundering obligations that reach insurers."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-utpa","question":"The ______ gives the state its authority to fine, issue cease and desist orders, and impose penalties.","options":["Unfair Trade Practices Act","Advertising Code","Buyer\'s Guide","McCarran-Ferguson Act"],"answer":"Unfair Trade Practices Act","topic":"Unfair Trade Practices Act","explanation":"The UTPA is the state\'s enforcement hammer — fines, cease-and-desist orders, penalties. Note: in Florida, rebating is legal under strict conditions (§626.572), so it is NOT an unfair trade practice there."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-utpa","question":"Which of the following would NOT be found under the Unfair Trade Practices Act?","options":["Rebating","False advertising","Coercion","Unfair discrimination"],"answer":"Rebating","topic":"Unfair Trade Practices Act","explanation":"The UTPA is the state\'s enforcement hammer — fines, cease-and-desist orders, penalties. Note: in Florida, rebating is legal under strict conditions (§626.572), so it is NOT an unfair trade practice there."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-lloyds","question":"Which organization is NOT itself an insurer, but a marketplace where member syndicates underwrite risks?","options":["Lloyd\'s of London","Blue Cross Blue Shield","A mutual insurance company","A stock insurance company"],"answer":"Lloyd\'s of London","topic":"Lloyd\'s of London","explanation":"Lloyd\'s is not an insurer or service provider — it\'s a marketplace where member syndicates underwrite risks."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-lloyds","question":"Which of the following is NOT a service provider?","options":["Lloyd\'s of London","An HMO","A PPO","Blue Cross Blue Shield"],"answer":"Lloyd\'s of London","topic":"Lloyd\'s of London","explanation":"Lloyd\'s is not an insurer or service provider — it\'s a marketplace where member syndicates underwrite risks."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-industrial","question":"Industrial (home service) life insurance is characterized by:","options":["Relatively small face amounts with premiums collected frequently by an agent","Large face amounts with annual premiums","Coverage available only to factory workers","Policies sold exclusively online"],"answer":"Relatively small face amounts with premiums collected frequently by an agent","topic":"Industrial Insurance","explanation":"Industrial (home service) insurance = small face amounts with premiums collected frequently (weekly/monthly), often at the insured\'s home."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-industrial","question":"Which is typical of industrial insurance?","options":["Small face amounts","Million-dollar minimum coverage","No premium payments","Group underwriting only"],"answer":"Small face amounts","topic":"Industrial Insurance","explanation":"Industrial (home service) insurance = small face amounts with premiums collected frequently (weekly/monthly), often at the insured\'s home."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-standards","question":"Which of the following is NOT a standard producers are expected to follow to protect consumers and promote suitable sales?","options":["Assessing the prospect\'s financial ability to pay commissions","Selling to the customer\'s needs","Determining the suitability of recommended products","Providing full and accurate disclosure"],"answer":"Assessing the prospect\'s financial ability to pay commissions","topic":"Suitability Standards","explanation":"Producers must sell to needs, verify suitability, and disclose fully. The client\'s ability to pay COMMISSIONS is never a standard — commissions come from the insurer."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-standards","question":"Before recommending a policy, a producer must primarily determine that:","options":["The product suits the client\'s needs and financial situation","The product pays the highest available commission","The client can be persuaded quickly","The insurer is headquartered in the client\'s state"],"answer":"The product suits the client\'s needs and financial situation","topic":"Suitability Standards","explanation":"Producers must sell to needs, verify suitability, and disclose fully. The client\'s ability to pay COMMISSIONS is never a standard — commissions come from the insurer."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-mccarran","question":"Which law laid the basis for the principle that state governments are the primary regulators of the insurance industry?","options":["The McCarran-Ferguson Act","The USA Patriot Act","The Affordable Care Act","The Sherman Antitrust Act"],"answer":"The McCarran-Ferguson Act","topic":"McCarran-Ferguson Act","explanation":"McCarran-Ferguson (1945) established that the states, not the federal government, are the primary regulators of insurance."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"d1m2-mccarran","question":"The McCarran-Ferguson Act provides that:","options":["Insurance is regulated by the states rather than the federal government","All insurers must register with the SEC","The federal government sets minimum premium rates","Insurance advertising is exempt from regulation"],"answer":"Insurance is regulated by the states rather than the federal government","topic":"McCarran-Ferguson Act","explanation":"McCarran-Ferguson (1945) established that the states, not the federal government, are the primary regulators of insurance."},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"ins-reinsure","topic":"Reinsurance","explanation":"Reinsurance is company-to-company. The insurer transferring (giving away) the risk is the CEDING company; the company accepting it is the reinsurer.","question":"ABC Insurance transfers part of a risk it has written to XYZ Insurance. In this arrangement, ABC is the:","options":["Ceding company","Reinsurer","Fraternal insurer","Captive agent"],"answer":"Ceding company"},{"module":"Day 1 Module 2","group":"ins-fraternal","topic":"Fraternal Benefit Societies","explanation":"A fraternal benefit society must be a nonprofit with a lodge system featuring ritualistic work and a representative form of government (elected officers). Example: Knights of Columbus.","question":"To be characterized as a fraternal benefit society, an organization must have all of the following EXCEPT:","options":["Stockholders who receive dividends","Nonprofit status","A lodge system with ritualistic work","Elected officers (representative government)"],"answer":"Stockholders who receive dividends"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-adhesion","question":"Because the insurer drafts the policy and the applicant cannot negotiate its terms, courts construe any ambiguity against the insurer. This reflects which characteristic of insurance contracts?","options":["It is a contract of adhesion","It is an aleatory contract","It is a unilateral contract","It is a valued contract"],"answer":"It is a contract of adhesion","topic":"Contract of Adhesion","explanation":"The insurer writes the contract; the applicant takes it or leaves it. Because of this, courts construe ambiguities AGAINST the insurer."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-adhesion","question":"An insurance policy is often called a \\"take it or leave it\\" contract. The legal term for this is a contract of:","options":["Adhesion","Indemnity","Subrogation","Consideration"],"answer":"Adhesion","topic":"Contract of Adhesion","explanation":"The insurer writes the contract; the applicant takes it or leaves it. Because of this, courts construe ambiguities AGAINST the insurer."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-aleatory","question":"Dario has paid only $2,000 in premiums when his $300,000 life policy pays out. The fact that the values exchanged may be very unequal — and depend on an uncertain event — makes the contract:","options":["Aleatory","Unilateral","Conditional","Adhesive"],"answer":"Aleatory","topic":"Aleatory Contract","explanation":"Aleatory = the exchange of value is unequal and depends on an uncertain event. Small premiums can buy a large benefit — or no benefit at all."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-aleatory","question":"Which feature of an insurance contract means there is an element of chance for both parties, and the dollars given by each side may not be equal?","options":["Aleatory","Consideration","Warranty","Estoppel"],"answer":"Aleatory","topic":"Aleatory Contract","explanation":"Aleatory = the exchange of value is unequal and depends on an uncertain event. Small premiums can buy a large benefit — or no benefit at all."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-unilateral","question":"In an insurance contract, only the insurer makes a legally enforceable promise — the insured can stop paying at any time without being sued. This makes the contract:","options":["Unilateral","Bilateral","Aleatory","Voidable"],"answer":"Unilateral","topic":"Unilateral Contract","explanation":"Only the insurer makes an enforceable promise. The insured can stop paying without breach — only the insurer can be sued for non-performance."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-unilateral","question":"In which type of contract can only one party be held liable in court for failing to perform?","options":["Unilateral","Bilateral","Adhesion","Valued"],"answer":"Unilateral","topic":"Unilateral Contract","explanation":"Only the insurer makes an enforceable promise. The insured can stop paying without breach — only the insurer can be sued for non-performance."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-interest","question":"At what point must insurable interest exist in a life or health insurance contract?","options":["At the inception of the policy","At the time of the claim","Both at inception and at claim","At each premium due date"],"answer":"At the inception of the policy","topic":"Insurable Interest","explanation":"Insurable interest must exist at the policy\'s INCEPTION (not at claim time), and it means the owner would suffer a real financial loss from the insured\'s death or disability."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-interest","question":"Which statement accurately describes insurable interest?","options":["The policy owner must expect to suffer a loss if the insured dies or becomes disabled","The policy owner must expect to benefit from the insured\'s death","A beneficiary always has an insurable interest in the insured by definition","The insured must be related to the beneficiary by blood or marriage"],"answer":"The policy owner must expect to suffer a loss if the insured dies or becomes disabled","topic":"Insurable Interest","explanation":"Insurable interest must exist at the policy\'s INCEPTION (not at claim time), and it means the owner would suffer a real financial loss from the insured\'s death or disability."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-interest","question":"Tia wants to insure the life of her business partner, whose death would create a serious financial loss for her. Does Tia have an insurable interest?","options":["Yes — she would suffer a financial loss if the partner died","No — only family members can have insurable interest","Only if the partner names her as beneficiary","Only if the partnership is incorporated"],"answer":"Yes — she would suffer a financial loss if the partner died","topic":"Insurable Interest","explanation":"Insurable interest must exist at the policy\'s INCEPTION (not at claim time), and it means the owner would suffer a real financial loss from the insured\'s death or disability."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-parole","question":"An applicant claims her agent verbally promised benefits that don\'t appear in the written policy. Which rule prevents oral statements from changing the written contract?","options":["The parole evidence rule","The free look provision","The doctrine of estoppel","The right of subrogation"],"answer":"The parole evidence rule","topic":"Parole Evidence Rule","explanation":"A written contract cannot be changed by oral evidence. Verbal promises that aren\'t in the policy don\'t count."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-parole","question":"What does the parole evidence rule provide?","options":["A written contract cannot be changed or modified by oral evidence","Verbal agreements always override the written contract","Contracts may be amended by either party at any time","Insurance contracts must be read aloud at delivery"],"answer":"A written contract cannot be changed or modified by oral evidence","topic":"Parole Evidence Rule","explanation":"A written contract cannot be changed by oral evidence. Verbal promises that aren\'t in the policy don\'t count."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-competent","question":"What makes an insurer a competent party to a contract?","options":["It is licensed or authorized by the state","It is registered with the NAIC","It is listed on a stock exchange","It maintains an office in every state"],"answer":"It is licensed or authorized by the state","topic":"Competent Parties","explanation":"An insurer is competent when licensed/authorized by the state. A person is incompetent when intoxicated, severely impaired, or (generally) a minor."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-competent","question":"Which of the following persons would NOT be considered competent to enter into an insurance contract?","options":["A 30-year-old who is heavily intoxicated at the time of application","A sober 40-year-old accountant","A 52-year-old retiree of sound mind","A licensed insurance company with a certificate of authority"],"answer":"A 30-year-old who is heavily intoxicated at the time of application","topic":"Competent Parties","explanation":"An insurer is competent when licensed/authorized by the state. A person is incompetent when intoxicated, severely impaired, or (generally) a minor."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-signatures","question":"Olive applies for a life policy on her employee Frank and names Frank\'s husband as beneficiary. Whose signatures must appear on the application?","options":["Olive\'s and Frank\'s","Only Olive\'s","Only Frank\'s","Olive\'s, Frank\'s, and the beneficiary\'s"],"answer":"Olive\'s and Frank\'s","topic":"Application Signatures","explanation":"Third-party policies require BOTH the applicant/owner\'s and the insured\'s signatures. The beneficiary never needs to sign."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-signatures","question":"When a business owner takes out life insurance on a key employee, the application must be signed by:","options":["Both the owner (as applicant) and the insured employee","The owner alone","The employee alone","The beneficiary and the agent"],"answer":"Both the owner (as applicant) and the insured employee","topic":"Application Signatures","explanation":"Third-party policies require BOTH the applicant/owner\'s and the insured\'s signatures. The beneficiary never needs to sign."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-authority","question":"The authority an agent is never given in writing, but which common sense dictates the agent must have to carry out routine business, is called:","options":["Implied authority","Express authority","Apparent authority","Statutory authority"],"answer":"Implied authority","topic":"Agent Authority","explanation":"Express = written in the agency contract. Implied = not written but necessary for routine business. Apparent = created by appearances the public reasonably relies on (e.g., a terminated agent still using company materials)."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-authority","question":"Rita was terminated by her insurer on May 1 but kept soliciting applications with her old company materials, and the public reasonably believed she still represented the company. The authority created by these circumstances is:","options":["Apparent authority","Express authority","Implied authority","Residual authority"],"answer":"Apparent authority","topic":"Agent Authority","explanation":"Express = written in the agency contract. Implied = not written but necessary for routine business. Apparent = created by appearances the public reasonably relies on (e.g., a terminated agent still using company materials)."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-authority","question":"The authority specifically granted to an agent in writing in the agency agreement is:","options":["Express authority","Implied authority","Apparent authority","Assumed authority"],"answer":"Express authority","topic":"Agent Authority","explanation":"Express = written in the agency contract. Implied = not written but necessary for routine business. Apparent = created by appearances the public reasonably relies on (e.g., a terminated agent still using company materials)."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-subrogation","question":"After paying a claim, an insurer acquires the insured\'s right to sue the third party who caused the loss. This right is called:","options":["Subrogation","Assignment","Estoppel","Reinstatement"],"answer":"Subrogation","topic":"Subrogation","explanation":"After paying a claim, the insurer takes over the insured\'s right to recover from the third party who caused the loss. It exists in INDEMNITY contracts, not valued contracts."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-subrogation","question":"The right of subrogation is found in which type of contract?","options":["Indemnity contracts","Valued contracts","Unilateral contracts only","Participating contracts"],"answer":"Indemnity contracts","topic":"Subrogation","explanation":"After paying a claim, the insurer takes over the insured\'s right to recover from the third party who caused the loss. It exists in INDEMNITY contracts, not valued contracts."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-valued","question":"Which of the following policies is NOT a valued contract?","options":["A medical expense policy","A life insurance policy","An AD&D policy","A disability income policy"],"answer":"A medical expense policy","topic":"Valued vs. Reimbursement","explanation":"Valued contracts (life, AD&D, disability income) pay a stated amount. Medical expense policies reimburse actual loss — they are NOT valued contracts."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-valued","question":"A contract that pays a stated, predetermined amount when a defined event occurs — regardless of the actual financial loss — is a:","options":["Valued contract","Reimbursement contract","Contract of indemnity","Conditional receipt"],"answer":"Valued contract","topic":"Valued vs. Reimbursement","explanation":"Valued contracts (life, AD&D, disability income) pay a stated amount. Medical expense policies reimburse actual loss — they are NOT valued contracts."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-personal","question":"Which statement about a life insurance contract is TRUE?","options":["It is not a personal contract, so ownership can be transferred or given away","It is a personal contract that can never change hands","It can only be assigned to a blood relative","It terminates automatically if ownership changes"],"answer":"It is not a personal contract, so ownership can be transferred or given away","topic":"Not a Personal Contract","explanation":"Life insurance is NOT a personal contract — ownership can be transferred or assigned, even to someone without insurable interest."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-personal","question":"Unlike property insurance, a life insurance policy can be assigned to someone with no insurable interest in the insured. This is because life insurance is:","options":["Not a personal contract","A bilateral contract","A contract of indemnity","An oral contract"],"answer":"Not a personal contract","topic":"Not a Personal Contract","explanation":"Life insurance is NOT a personal contract — ownership can be transferred or assigned, even to someone without insurable interest."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-beneficiary","question":"Hugo named his sister Ana as primary beneficiary and Ana\'s daughter Sofia as secondary. Ana dies before Hugo, and Hugo never updates the policy. At Hugo\'s death, the proceeds go to:","options":["Sofia, as the contingent beneficiary","Ana\'s estate","Hugo\'s estate","The state unclaimed property fund"],"answer":"Sofia, as the contingent beneficiary","topic":"Beneficiary Succession","explanation":"If the primary beneficiary dies before the insured, proceeds go to the contingent (secondary) beneficiary — not the primary\'s estate or heirs."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-beneficiary","question":"If the primary beneficiary dies before the insured and no changes are made, the death benefit is paid to:","options":["The contingent (secondary) beneficiary","The insured\'s estate automatically","The primary beneficiary\'s heirs","The insurer\'s surplus fund"],"answer":"The contingent (secondary) beneficiary","topic":"Beneficiary Succession","explanation":"If the primary beneficiary dies before the insured, proceeds go to the contingent (secondary) beneficiary — not the primary\'s estate or heirs."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-stoli","question":"An investor persuades Catherine, 78, to take out a new life policy. The investor funds the premiums and is named beneficiary. This arrangement is:","options":["A STOLI (stranger-originated life insurance) arrangement","A legitimate key-person policy","A viatical settlement","An ordinary third-party ownership arrangement"],"answer":"A STOLI (stranger-originated life insurance) arrangement","topic":"STOLI","explanation":"Stranger-originated life insurance: investors induce a stranger (often elderly) to take out a policy they fund and benefit from. Fraudulent because the investors have NO insurable interest."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"d2m1-stoli","question":"Why do many states treat STOLI arrangements as fraudulent?","options":["The investors have no insurable interest in the insured","The premiums are paid too quickly","The policies exceed state face-amount limits","The insured is always underage"],"answer":"The investors have no insurable interest in the insured","topic":"STOLI","explanation":"Stranger-originated life insurance: investors induce a stranger (often elderly) to take out a policy they fund and benefit from. Fraudulent because the investors have NO insurable interest."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"law-eo","topic":"E&O Insurance","explanation":"Errors & omissions (professional liability) insurance defends against groundless, false, or fraudulent lawsuits — it protects the AGENT/producer, not the applicant or insurer.","question":"Errors and omissions (E&O) insurance provides a defense against groundless or fraudulent lawsuits brought against:","options":["The agent","The applicant","The insurance company","The insured"],"answer":"The agent"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"law-authority","topic":"Agent Authority (Bank Trap)","explanation":"COURSE-KEY WARNING: standard texts define IMPLIED authority as \'not expressly granted but necessary to transact the principal\'s business\' — yet this course\'s bank marked \'implied\' WRONG on exactly this wording and apparently keys APPARENT. If you see this wording on a course quiz, answer apparent; on the state exam, the textbook answer for \'authority the agent must have to transact business though not expressly granted\' is IMPLIED. Flag the discrepancy to your instructor.","question":"[Course bank] What type of authority is not overtly extended but must be used to enable the agent to transact the business of the principal?","options":["Apparent (this bank\'s key — standard texts say implied!)","Express","Fiduciary","Assumed"],"answer":"Apparent (this bank\'s key — standard texts say implied!)"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 1","group":"law-competent","topic":"Competent Parties","explanation":"Competent parties: legally capable of contracting. An insurer with a Certificate of Authority is competent. Per this course\'s key, a person UNDER THE INFLUENCE is the incompetent party — an Alzheimer\'s diagnosis alone was NOT keyed as incompetence, and in Florida minors 15+ may contract for insurance.","question":"All of the following are considered competent parties EXCEPT:","options":["A 25-year-old under the influence of alcohol","An insurance company holding a certificate of authority from the state","A 17-year-old who just graduated from high school","A 52-year-old recently diagnosed with early Alzheimer\'s"],"answer":"A 25-year-old under the influence of alcohol"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-misrep-when","question":"During the selling process, serious problems of misrepresentation are MOST likely to occur at which stage?","options":["Presentation of recommendations","Prospecting","Fact-finding","Policy delivery"],"answer":"Presentation of recommendations","topic":"When Misrepresentation Happens","explanation":"Misrepresentation problems peak at the presentation of recommendations — when the producer is describing products and making claims about them."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-misrep-when","question":"At which point in the sales process must a producer be most careful that product claims are accurate?","options":["When presenting recommendations to the client","When scheduling the first appointment","When mailing a birthday card","When filing the application"],"answer":"When presenting recommendations to the client","topic":"When Misrepresentation Happens","explanation":"Misrepresentation problems peak at the presentation of recommendations — when the producer is describing products and making claims about them."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-misrep","question":"An agent tells a prospect that a variable universal life policy is \\"basically the same thing as a mutual fund.\\" This statement is:","options":["Misrepresentation","Twisting","Rebating","Churning"],"answer":"Misrepresentation","topic":"Misrepresentation","explanation":"Any false or misleading statement about a policy — calling VUL a mutual fund, calling dividends guaranteed — is misrepresentation."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-misrep","question":"Telling a client that policy dividends are guaranteed, when they are not, is an example of:","options":["Misrepresentation","Defamation","Coercion","Rebating"],"answer":"Misrepresentation","topic":"Misrepresentation","explanation":"Any false or misleading statement about a policy — calling VUL a mutual fund, calling dividends guaranteed — is misrepresentation."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-presentation","question":"Which of the following does NOT belong in a product presentation?","options":["Pressure","Accurate product information","Disclosure documents","Answers to the client\'s questions"],"answer":"Pressure","topic":"The Sales Presentation","explanation":"The presentation\'s goal is to EDUCATE so the client decides — pressure and \'selling\' don\'t belong. Educate, disclose, answer honestly."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-presentation","question":"What is the main goal of a sales presentation?","options":["To educate clients, empowering them to make their own decisions","To close the sale before the client can compare options","To collect the first premium as quickly as possible","To demonstrate the agent\'s product knowledge"],"answer":"To educate clients, empowering them to make their own decisions","topic":"The Sales Presentation","explanation":"The presentation\'s goal is to EDUCATE so the client decides — pressure and \'selling\' don\'t belong. Educate, disclose, answer honestly."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-presentation","question":"What should a producer NOT do during a presentation?","options":["Sell a policy","Educate the client","Disclose product limitations","Answer questions honestly"],"answer":"Sell a policy","topic":"The Sales Presentation","explanation":"The presentation\'s goal is to EDUCATE so the client decides — pressure and \'selling\' don\'t belong. Educate, disclose, answer honestly."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-homeoffice","question":"All of the following are part of the Home Office underwriting process EXCEPT:","options":["The applicant\'s analyst report","Review of the application","The MIB report","Medical examination results"],"answer":"The applicant\'s analyst report","topic":"Home Office Underwriting","explanation":"Underwriters use the application, agent\'s report, MIB report, medical exams, and physician statements. A stock \'analyst report\' is not part of underwriting."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-homeoffice","question":"Which of the following would a home office underwriter NOT rely on when evaluating an application?","options":["The applicant\'s stock analyst report","The agent\'s report","The completed application","An attending physician statement"],"answer":"The applicant\'s stock analyst report","topic":"Home Office Underwriting","explanation":"Underwriters use the application, agent\'s report, MIB report, medical exams, and physician statements. A stock \'analyst report\' is not part of underwriting."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-ethics","question":"Ethics is best defined as:","options":["Standards of conduct and moral judgment governing how we deal with others","The body of state insurance statutes","A company\'s internal pricing rules","Federal regulations on advertising"],"answer":"Standards of conduct and moral judgment governing how we deal with others","topic":"Ethics","explanation":"Ethics = standards of conduct and moral judgment governing how we deal with others — beyond what laws require."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-ethics","question":"Standards of conduct, moral judgment, and guidance on interacting with fellow members of a profession define:","options":["Ethics","Compliance","Solicitation","Underwriting"],"answer":"Ethics","topic":"Ethics","explanation":"Ethics = standards of conduct and moral judgment governing how we deal with others — beyond what laws require."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-naic","question":"What does NAIC stand for?","options":["National Association of Insurance Commissioners","National Alliance of Insurance Companies","North American Insurance Council","National Agency for Insurance Compliance"],"answer":"National Association of Insurance Commissioners","topic":"NAIC Purpose","explanation":"NAIC = National Association of Insurance Commissioners. Its objective is uniformity in state insurance regulation via model laws."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-naic","question":"An objective of the National Association of Insurance Commissioners is to:","options":["Encourage uniformity in state insurance regulation","License agents in all fifty states","Set federal premium taxes","Underwrite high-risk applicants"],"answer":"Encourage uniformity in state insurance regulation","topic":"NAIC Purpose","explanation":"NAIC = National Association of Insurance Commissioners. Its objective is uniformity in state insurance regulation via model laws."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-illustrations","question":"Which of the following is NOT a provision of the NAIC\'s Life Insurance Illustrations Model Regulation?","options":["The words \\"vanish\\" and \\"vanishing premium\\" may be used sparingly in illustrations","Illustrations must distinguish guaranteed from non-guaranteed values","Illustrations must be clearly labeled","Certain misleading terminology is prohibited"],"answer":"The words \\"vanish\\" and \\"vanishing premium\\" may be used sparingly in illustrations","topic":"Illustrations Regulation","explanation":"The NAIC model regulation prohibits misleading terms like \'vanish\' and \'vanishing premium\' entirely — not even \'sparingly\' — and requires guaranteed vs. non-guaranteed values to be distinguished."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-illustrations","question":"Under the NAIC model regulation on illustrations, which phrase is prohibited?","options":["\\"Vanishing premium\\"","\\"Guaranteed values\\"","\\"Cash surrender value\\"","\\"Death benefit\\""],"answer":"\\"Vanishing premium\\"","topic":"Illustrations Regulation","explanation":"The NAIC model regulation prohibits misleading terms like \'vanish\' and \'vanishing premium\' entirely — not even \'sparingly\' — and requires guaranteed vs. non-guaranteed values to be distinguished."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-preprinted","question":"Preprinted materials are recommended for sales presentations because:","options":["They have generally been reviewed for compliance","They let the agent avoid answering the client\'s questions","They are cheaper than custom materials","They guarantee the sale will close"],"answer":"They have generally been reviewed for compliance","topic":"Preprinted Materials","explanation":"Company preprinted materials are preferred because they\'ve been reviewed for regulatory compliance — homemade handouts haven\'t."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-preprinted","question":"Why should a producer favor company-approved preprinted materials over homemade handouts?","options":["Company materials have been vetted for regulatory compliance","Homemade materials are illegal in all states","Preprinted materials earn higher commissions","Clients are not permitted to keep custom documents"],"answer":"Company materials have been vetted for regulatory compliance","topic":"Preprinted Materials","explanation":"Company preprinted materials are preferred because they\'ve been reviewed for regulatory compliance — homemade handouts haven\'t."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-disclosure","question":"The purpose behind full disclosure requirements is to:","options":["Help the client make an informed decision","Protect the agent from competition","Shorten the sales process","Increase policy premiums"],"answer":"Help the client make an informed decision","topic":"Full Disclosure","explanation":"Disclosure documents exist for one reason: to help the client make an informed decision."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-disclosure","question":"Documents like the policy summary and Buyer\'s Guide are given to applicants so that they can:","options":["Make an informed purchase decision","Waive the free look period","Lock in a guaranteed dividend","Avoid the underwriting process"],"answer":"Make an informed purchase decision","topic":"Full Disclosure","explanation":"Disclosure documents exist for one reason: to help the client make an informed decision."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-rebating","question":"An agent gives his client four concert tickets as a thank-you for purchasing a policy. This is an example of:","options":["Rebating","Churning","Twisting","Defamation"],"answer":"Rebating","topic":"Rebating","explanation":"Giving the client anything of value (gifts, tickets, commission kickbacks) as an inducement to buy = rebating. In Florida it\'s legal ONLY under the strict conditions of §626.572."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-rebating","question":"Returning a portion of the commission to a client as an inducement to buy a policy is called:","options":["Rebating","Coercion","Misrepresentation","Concealment"],"answer":"Rebating","topic":"Rebating","explanation":"Giving the client anything of value (gifts, tickets, commission kickbacks) as an inducement to buy = rebating. In Florida it\'s legal ONLY under the strict conditions of §626.572."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-churning","question":"An agent convinces a client to surrender an existing policy and buy a replacement from the SAME insurer, mainly to generate a new commission. This practice is:","options":["Churning","Twisting","Rebating","Subrogation"],"answer":"Churning","topic":"Churning","explanation":"Churning = replacing a policy with another from the SAME insurer mainly to earn new commissions. (Twisting is the same scheme with a DIFFERENT insurer.)"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-churning","question":"Churning is best described as:","options":["Replacing a policy with another from the same insurer with the intent of earning additional commissions","Replacing a policy with one from a different insurer","Selling multiple policies to one household","Backdating an application to save age"],"answer":"Replacing a policy with another from the same insurer with the intent of earning additional commissions","topic":"Churning","explanation":"Churning = replacing a policy with another from the SAME insurer mainly to earn new commissions. (Twisting is the same scheme with a DIFFERENT insurer.)"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-solicitation","question":"Which of the following activities are included in the solicitation of insurance?","options":["Presenting proposals, describing benefits, and urging a prospect to apply","Only the signing of the final application","Only paid television advertising","Only activities performed inside the insurer\'s office"],"answer":"Presenting proposals, describing benefits, and urging a prospect to apply","topic":"Solicitation","explanation":"Solicitation includes presenting proposals, describing benefits, and urging prospects to apply — anything that attempts to induce the purchase of insurance."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-solicitation","question":"Inviting prospects at a seminar to apply for coverage is part of:","options":["Solicitation","Underwriting","Claims adjustment","Policy delivery"],"answer":"Solicitation","topic":"Solicitation","explanation":"Solicitation includes presenting proposals, describing benefits, and urging prospects to apply — anything that attempts to induce the purchase of insurance."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-freelook","question":"The period specified in the free look provision begins:","options":["When the policy is delivered","When the application is signed","When the policy is issued","When the first claim is filed"],"answer":"When the policy is delivered","topic":"Free Look","explanation":"The free look period starts at policy DELIVERY — not issue, not application."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-freelook","question":"Yara\'s policy was issued on June 1 and delivered to her on June 9. Her free look period runs from:","options":["June 9 — the date of delivery","June 1 — the date of issue","The date she signed the application","The first premium due date"],"answer":"June 9 — the date of delivery","topic":"Free Look","explanation":"The free look period starts at policy DELIVERY — not issue, not application."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-educate","question":"The producer should educate the applicant on all of the following EXCEPT:","options":["How the DFS works with the CFO","The need for accuracy and honesty on the application","The meanings of terms such as waiver of premium","Why the requested information is required"],"answer":"How the DFS works with the CFO","topic":"Educating the Applicant","explanation":"Producers should explain honesty requirements, policy terms, and why information is collected. Internal department mechanics (DFS/CFO) aren\'t part of it."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-educate","question":"Which of the following SHOULD a producer review with an applicant?","options":["The need for honesty, the meaning of policy terms, and why information is collected","The agent\'s commission percentage on the sale","Other clients\' claim histories","The underwriter\'s personal contact information"],"answer":"The need for honesty, the meaning of policy terms, and why information is collected","topic":"Educating the Applicant","explanation":"Producers should explain honesty requirements, policy terms, and why information is collected. Internal department mechanics (DFS/CFO) aren\'t part of it."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-uwexplain","question":"When briefly explaining the underwriting process to a client, which of the following is NOT part of underwriting?","options":["Salary requirements","Medical examinations","MIB reports","Review of the application"],"answer":"Salary requirements","topic":"Explaining Underwriting","explanation":"Underwriting draws on the application, medical exams, MIB, and physician statements. Salary requirements and commissions are not underwriting sources."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"d2m2-uwexplain","question":"Which of the following is NOT a source of underwriting information?","options":["The agent\'s commission schedule","The application","The MIB report","An attending physician statement"],"answer":"The agent\'s commission schedule","topic":"Explaining Underwriting","explanation":"Underwriting draws on the application, medical exams, MIB, and physician statements. Salary requirements and commissions are not underwriting sources."},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"eth-insuring","topic":"The Insuring Clause","explanation":"The insuring clause sits at the front of the policy, signed by the company\'s president and secretary — it is the insurer\'s basic promise to pay benefits if a covered condition occurs.","question":"The insurer\'s promise to pay, found on the first page of the policy and signed by the company\'s officers, is the:","options":["Insuring clause","Consideration clause","Entire contract clause","Free-look provision"],"answer":"Insuring clause"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"eth-uwfactors","topic":"Underwriting Factors","explanation":"Health underwriters consider physical condition, medical history, occupation, personal habits/moral hazards — and yes, even the CREDIT rating (credit reports are part of the checks and balances). MARITAL STATUS is not an underwriting risk factor.","question":"Which of the following would probably NOT be considered in underwriting a health insurance risk?","options":["The individual\'s marital status","The individual\'s personal habits","The individual\'s credit rating","The individual\'s medical history"],"answer":"The individual\'s marital status"},{"module":"Day 2 Module 2","group":"eth-uwfactors","topic":"Underwriting Factors","explanation":"Primary health underwriting risk factors: physical condition, occupation, and moral hazards/lifestyle. Interest rates are a PREMIUM calculation factor (the I in MIST), not an underwriting risk factor about the applicant.","question":"Which of the following is NOT one of the primary risk factors used in health insurance underwriting?","options":["Interest rates","Physical condition","Moral hazards","Occupation"],"answer":"Interest rates"},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-types","question":"Hannah\'s agent walks her through the main categories of health insurance. Which of the following does NOT actually exist as a basic form of health coverage?","options":["Limited pay health","Medical expense insurance","Disability income insurance","Accidental death and dismemberment"],"answer":"Limited pay health","topic":"Basic Types of Health Coverage","explanation":"The three basic types (MAD): Medical expense, AD&D, and Disability income. \'Limited pay health\' is a made-up distractor."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-types","question":"The three basic types of health insurance coverage are:","options":["Medical expense, disability income, and accidental death and dismemberment","Medical expense, long-term care, and annuities","Disability income, workers\' compensation, and Medicare","Major medical, limited pay health, and AD&D"],"answer":"Medical expense, disability income, and accidental death and dismemberment","topic":"Basic Types of Health Coverage","explanation":"The three basic types (MAD): Medical expense, AD&D, and Disability income. \'Limited pay health\' is a made-up distractor."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-medex","question":"Medical expense insurance covers which of the following?","options":["Hospitalization, surgical, and physician services expenses","Lost income while the insured is disabled","A lump sum payable upon accidental death","Funeral and burial expenses"],"answer":"Hospitalization, surgical, and physician services expenses","topic":"Medical Expense Insurance","explanation":"Medical expense insurance pays actual healthcare costs — hospitalization, surgery, physician services, outpatient care — on a reimbursement basis."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-medex","question":"Theo needs ongoing physical therapy, regular lab work, and an occasional outpatient procedure. Which type of insurance pays these healthcare costs?","options":["Medical expense insurance","Disability income insurance","Accidental death and dismemberment insurance","Credit health insurance"],"answer":"Medical expense insurance","topic":"Medical Expense Insurance","explanation":"Medical expense insurance pays actual healthcare costs — hospitalization, surgery, physician services, outpatient care — on a reimbursement basis."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-di","question":"The primary purpose of disability income insurance is to:","options":["Replace income lost when the insured cannot work due to disability","Pay the medical expenses arising from a disability","Provide a lump sum benefit for accidental dismemberment","Reimburse hospital and surgical costs"],"answer":"Replace income lost when the insured cannot work due to disability","topic":"Disability Income Insurance","explanation":"DI replaces lost INCOME when the insured can\'t work. It never pays the medical bills caused by the disability — that\'s medical expense insurance\'s job."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-di","question":"Which statement about disability income insurance is TRUE?","options":["It excludes coverage for medical expenses arising from the disability","It reimburses the insured for hospital expenses during a disability","It pays benefits only for work-related disabilities","It pays a lump sum upon proof of permanent disability"],"answer":"It excludes coverage for medical expenses arising from the disability","topic":"Disability Income Insurance","explanation":"DI replaces lost INCOME when the insured can\'t work. It never pays the medical bills caused by the disability — that\'s medical expense insurance\'s job."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-di","question":"Carlos was injured and cannot work for eight months. Which coverage would replace his lost paycheck during this period?","options":["Disability income insurance","Medical expense insurance","AD&D insurance","Medicare supplement insurance"],"answer":"Disability income insurance","topic":"Disability Income Insurance","explanation":"DI replaces lost INCOME when the insured can\'t work. It never pays the medical bills caused by the disability — that\'s medical expense insurance\'s job."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-add","question":"Which statement about accidental death and dismemberment (AD&D) insurance is CORRECT?","options":["It pays a lump sum benefit if the insured dies or is dismembered in an accident","It reimburses medical expenses resulting from an accident","It replaces income lost due to an accidental injury","It pays benefits for death from sickness or accident alike"],"answer":"It pays a lump sum benefit if the insured dies or is dismembered in an accident","topic":"AD&D","explanation":"AD&D pays a lump sum for accidental death or dismemberment only — never sickness. It\'s the purest form of accident insurance."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-add","question":"AD&D insurance is considered:","options":["The purest form of accident insurance","A form of limited pay whole life insurance","A government-sponsored benefit program","A type of medical expense reimbursement plan"],"answer":"The purest form of accident insurance","topic":"AD&D","explanation":"AD&D pays a lump sum for accidental death or dismemberment only — never sickness. It\'s the purest form of accident insurance."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-purchase","question":"Group health insurance differs from individual health insurance in that group coverage is:","options":["Provided through a master contract issued to a specific group","Issued as a separate contract to each covered member","Available only through government programs","Always issued on a nonparticipating basis"],"answer":"Provided through a master contract issued to a specific group","topic":"How Coverage Is Purchased","explanation":"Individual = contract between insured and insurer. Group = one master contract covering a group. Government: Medicaid (state, for the needy), Medicare and OASDI (federal)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-purchase","question":"Which government health program is run by the states to provide coverage for low-income people?","options":["Medicaid","Medicare","OASDI","TRICARE"],"answer":"Medicaid","topic":"How Coverage Is Purchased","explanation":"Individual = contract between insured and insurer. Group = one master contract covering a group. Government: Medicaid (state, for the needy), Medicare and OASDI (federal)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-purchase","question":"Individual health insurance is issued as a contract between:","options":["The insured and a commercial insurer or service organization","The employer and the insurance company","The state government and the insured","The insured and the federal government"],"answer":"The insured and a commercial insurer or service organization","topic":"How Coverage Is Purchased","explanation":"Individual = contract between insured and insurer. Group = one master contract covering a group. Government: Medicaid (state, for the needy), Medicare and OASDI (federal)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-renew","question":"Which renewability provision provides the insured with the greatest degree of security?","options":["Noncancellable","Cancellable","Optionally renewable","Conditionally renewable"],"answer":"Noncancellable","topic":"Renewability Provisions","explanation":"From least to most protective (and cheapest to priciest): Cancellable → Optionally renewable → Conditionally renewable → Guaranteed renewable (must renew, premiums can rise by class) → Noncancellable (must renew, premiums fixed)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-renew","question":"Under a guaranteed renewable health policy, the insurer:","options":["Must renew the policy but may increase premiums for an entire class of insureds","May cancel the policy at any time with proper notice","Must renew the policy and may never increase the premium","May refuse to renew for any reason at the anniversary date"],"answer":"Must renew the policy but may increase premiums for an entire class of insureds","topic":"Renewability Provisions","explanation":"From least to most protective (and cheapest to priciest): Cancellable → Optionally renewable → Conditionally renewable → Guaranteed renewable (must renew, premiums can rise by class) → Noncancellable (must renew, premiums fixed)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-renew","question":"Which renewability classification is generally the LEAST expensive?","options":["Cancellable","Noncancellable","Guaranteed renewable","Conditionally renewable"],"answer":"Cancellable","topic":"Renewability Provisions","explanation":"From least to most protective (and cheapest to priciest): Cancellable → Optionally renewable → Conditionally renewable → Guaranteed renewable (must renew, premiums can rise by class) → Noncancellable (must renew, premiums fixed)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-mode","question":"Which premium payment mode results in the highest overall cost to the policyowner?","options":["Weekly","Annually","Semiannually","Quarterly"],"answer":"Weekly","topic":"Premium Modes","explanation":"Annual payment = lowest total cost. Each step more frequent adds expense; weekly is most expensive overall."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-mode","question":"Which premium payment mode results in the lowest overall cost to the policyowner?","options":["Annually","Monthly","Weekly","Quarterly"],"answer":"Annually","topic":"Premium Modes","explanation":"Annual payment = lowest total cost. Each step more frequent adds expense; weekly is most expensive overall."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-factors","question":"Life insurance premiums are built on mortality tables. What is the equivalent factor insurers use to price health insurance?","options":["Morbidity","Mortality","Liquidity","Volatility"],"answer":"Morbidity","topic":"Premium Factors (MIX-T)","explanation":"Premiums are built from Morbidity, Interest, eXpense, and Types of benefits. Morbidity (sickness rates) is health insurance\'s counterpart to life insurance\'s mortality."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-factors","question":"Which of the following lists the factors used to calculate health insurance premiums?","options":["Morbidity, interest, expense, and types of benefits","Mortality, dividends, claims, and reserves","Age, occupation, residence, and income","Interest, inflation, taxes, and commissions"],"answer":"Morbidity, interest, expense, and types of benefits","topic":"Premium Factors (MIX-T)","explanation":"Premiums are built from Morbidity, Interest, eXpense, and Types of benefits. Morbidity (sickness rates) is health insurance\'s counterpart to life insurance\'s mortality."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-factors","question":"Morbidity is best defined as:","options":["The rate of sickness or disease within a particular population","The rate of death within a particular population","The insurer\'s cost of doing business","The expected investment return on premiums"],"answer":"The rate of sickness or disease within a particular population","topic":"Premium Factors (MIX-T)","explanation":"Premiums are built from Morbidity, Interest, eXpense, and Types of benefits. Morbidity (sickness rates) is health insurance\'s counterpart to life insurance\'s mortality."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-par","question":"Which statement regarding participating and nonparticipating health insurance is CORRECT?","options":["Individual policies are typically nonparticipating, while group policies are typically participating","Individual policies are typically participating, while group policies are typically nonparticipating","All health insurance policies are participating","Participating policies never pay dividends"],"answer":"Individual policies are typically nonparticipating, while group policies are typically participating","topic":"Participating vs. Nonparticipating","explanation":"Individual health policies = nonparticipating. Group policies = participating — eligible for dividends (a refund of premium) or experience-rating refunds."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-par","question":"Policy dividends paid to policyholders of a mutual insurer are best described as:","options":["A refund of premium","Taxable investment income","A guaranteed contract benefit","A loan against the policy"],"answer":"A refund of premium","topic":"Participating vs. Nonparticipating","explanation":"Individual health policies = nonparticipating. Group policies = participating — eligible for dividends (a refund of premium) or experience-rating refunds."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-divfactors","question":"Which two major factors determine whether dividends or experience-rating refunds are payable?","options":["Expenses and claims costs","Age and gender of insureds","Interest rates and taxes","Policy size and premium mode"],"answer":"Expenses and claims costs","topic":"Dividend Determinants","explanation":"Two factors decide whether dividends/experience refunds are payable: the insurer\'s EXPENSES and the group\'s CLAIMS COSTS."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-divfactors","question":"A group health plan is most likely to receive an experience-rating refund or premium credit when:","options":["The group\'s claims costs are low","The group\'s members are mostly young males","Interest rates rise during the year","The employer pays premiums annually"],"answer":"The group\'s claims costs are low","topic":"Dividend Determinants","explanation":"Two factors decide whether dividends/experience refunds are payable: the insurer\'s EXPENSES and the group\'s CLAIMS COSTS."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-reserves","question":"On an insurance company\'s books, reserves are treated as:","options":["A liability","An asset","Surplus","Earned income"],"answer":"A liability","topic":"Reserves","explanation":"Reserves are a LIABILITY on the insurer\'s books. Premium reserves = losses not yet occurred but premium received. Loss reserves = losses occurred but not yet settled."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-reserves","question":"Premium reserves represent the insurer\'s obligation for:","options":["Potential losses that have not yet occurred but for which premiums have already been received","Losses that have occurred but have not yet been settled","Dividends owed to participating policyholders","Commissions owed to producers"],"answer":"Potential losses that have not yet occurred but for which premiums have already been received","topic":"Reserves","explanation":"Reserves are a LIABILITY on the insurer\'s books. Premium reserves = losses not yet occurred but premium received. Loss reserves = losses occurred but not yet settled."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-reserves","question":"Loss reserves represent the insurer\'s liability for:","options":["Losses that have occurred but for which settlement is not yet complete","Losses that have not yet occurred","Future premium refunds to policyowners","Anticipated underwriting expenses"],"answer":"Losses that have occurred but for which settlement is not yet complete","topic":"Reserves","explanation":"Reserves are a LIABILITY on the insurer\'s books. Premium reserves = losses not yet occurred but premium received. Loss reserves = losses occurred but not yet settled."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-contracts","question":"Imani\'s policy promises a flat $1,200 per month while she is totally disabled, regardless of what her actual expenses are. This makes her policy a ______ contract.","options":["Valued","Reimbursement","Participating","Conditional"],"answer":"Valued","topic":"Valued vs. Reimbursement","explanation":"A policy paying a stated amount (e.g., $X/month while disabled) is VALUED. Medical expense insurance pays actual loss — a contract of REIMBURSEMENT (indemnity)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-contracts","question":"Medical expense insurance is best described as:","options":["A contract of reimbursement that pays based on the actual amount of loss","A valued contract that pays a predetermined amount","A participating contract that pays annual dividends","A service contract that pays providers in advance"],"answer":"A contract of reimbursement that pays based on the actual amount of loss","topic":"Valued vs. Reimbursement","explanation":"A policy paying a stated amount (e.g., $X/month while disabled) is VALUED. Medical expense insurance pays actual loss — a contract of REIMBURSEMENT (indemnity)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-contracts","question":"Which of the following are considered valued contracts?","options":["Life insurance, AD&D, and disability income insurance","Medical expense and Medicare supplement insurance","Group health and individual health insurance","Long-term care and major medical insurance"],"answer":"Life insurance, AD&D, and disability income insurance","topic":"Valued vs. Reimbursement","explanation":"A policy paying a stated amount (e.g., $X/month while disabled) is VALUED. Medical expense insurance pays actual loss — a contract of REIMBURSEMENT (indemnity)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-subsidy","question":"Under the Affordable Care Act, premium subsidies are available to individuals and families whose income falls within:","options":["100% to 400% of the Federal Poverty Level","50% to 100% of the Federal Poverty Level","138% to 250% of the Federal Poverty Level","200% to 500% of the Federal Poverty Level"],"answer":"100% to 400% of the Federal Poverty Level","topic":"ACA Subsidies","explanation":"Subsidies: income between 100% and 400% of the Federal Poverty Level. Medicaid expansion: at or below 138% FPL."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-subsidy","question":"The ACA expanded Medicaid eligibility to nearly all individuals whose income is at or below what percentage of the poverty level?","options":["138%","100%","250%","400%"],"answer":"138%","topic":"ACA Subsidies","explanation":"Subsidies: income between 100% and 400% of the Federal Poverty Level. Medicaid expansion: at or below 138% FPL."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-reforms","question":"Under the Affordable Care Act, children must be allowed to remain on a parent\'s health plan until age:","options":["26","21","18","25"],"answer":"26","topic":"ACA Reforms","explanation":"No denial for preexisting conditions; children stay on a parent\'s plan to age 26; the $695 individual mandate tax was zeroed out by the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act starting 2018."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-reforms","question":"Which statement regarding preexisting conditions under the ACA is TRUE?","options":["Insurers cannot deny coverage to anyone based on a preexisting condition","Insurers may deny coverage to adults but not children with preexisting conditions","Insurers may impose a permanent exclusion for preexisting conditions","Preexisting condition protections apply only to group plans"],"answer":"Insurers cannot deny coverage to anyone based on a preexisting condition","topic":"ACA Reforms","explanation":"No denial for preexisting conditions; children stay on a parent\'s plan to age 26; the $695 individual mandate tax was zeroed out by the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act starting 2018."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-reforms","question":"The individual mandate tax penalty was reduced to zero beginning in 2018 by:","options":["The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act","The Affordable Care Act itself","HIPAA","The Social Security Act"],"answer":"The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act","topic":"ACA Reforms","explanation":"No denial for preexisting conditions; children stay on a parent\'s plan to age 26; the $695 individual mandate tax was zeroed out by the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act starting 2018."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-employer","question":"The ACA employer mandate applies to employers with at least how many full-time employees?","options":["50","25","100","10"],"answer":"50","topic":"ACA Employer Mandate","explanation":"Employers with 50+ full-time employees must offer qualifying coverage to at least 95% of them and their dependents, or face $2,000/worker/year if any worker takes federal assistance."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-employer","question":"An employer subject to the ACA mandate that fails to offer qualifying coverage may face an annual penalty of:","options":["$2,000 per worker if any worker receives federal assistance to buy insurance","$695 per worker regardless of circumstances","$10,000 flat fine per year","10% of total payroll"],"answer":"$2,000 per worker if any worker receives federal assistance to buy insurance","topic":"ACA Employer Mandate","explanation":"Employers with 50+ full-time employees must offer qualifying coverage to at least 95% of them and their dependents, or face $2,000/worker/year if any worker takes federal assistance."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"m1-aca-employer","question":"Under the employer mandate, qualifying coverage must be offered to at least what percentage of full-time employees and their dependents?","options":["95%","100%","75%","50%"],"answer":"95%","topic":"ACA Employer Mandate","explanation":"Employers with 50+ full-time employees must offer qualifying coverage to at least 95% of them and their dependents, or face $2,000/worker/year if any worker takes federal assistance."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 1","group":"hi-premfactors","topic":"Premium Factors","explanation":"The three SECONDARY premium factors in health insurance: claims experience, age & sex of the insured, and benefit amounts. \'Salary benefits\' is not one of them. (Primary factors = morbidity, interest, expenses, type of benefits — MIST.)","question":"Which of the following is NOT one of the three secondary premium factors in health insurance?","options":["Salary benefits","Claims experience","Age and sex of the insured","Benefit amounts"],"answer":"Salary benefits"},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-commercial","question":"After surgery, Russ submits his hospital bills and receives a check made out to him personally. Which type of organization handles claims this way?","options":["A commercial insurer","A health maintenance organization","A preferred provider organization","An administrative-services-only plan"],"answer":"A commercial insurer","topic":"Commercial Insurers","explanation":"Commercial insurers use the REIMBURSEMENT approach — the insured submits bills and is paid back directly. HMOs/PPOs provide services instead."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-commercial","question":"Commercial insurance companies market health insurance using which approach?","options":["The reimbursement approach, in which policyholders receive care and submit bills for reimbursement","The prepayment approach, in which providers are paid before care is given","The service approach, in which benefits are provided as services","The capitation approach, in which providers receive a flat monthly fee"],"answer":"The reimbursement approach, in which policyholders receive care and submit bills for reimbursement","topic":"Commercial Insurers","explanation":"Commercial insurers use the REIMBURSEMENT approach — the insured submits bills and is paid back directly. HMOs/PPOs provide services instead."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-assignment","question":"The right of assignment in a health insurance policy allows:","options":["The insurance company to pay the medical provider directly","The insured to transfer ownership of the policy to a relative","The insurer to cancel the policy upon nonpayment","The provider to bill the patient for any unpaid balance"],"answer":"The insurance company to pay the medical provider directly","topic":"Right of Assignment","explanation":"Assignment lets the insurer pay the medical provider directly so the insured doesn\'t pay up front. It changes who gets the check, not the contract\'s nature."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-assignment","question":"The main advantage of the right of assignment is that it:","options":["Reduces the policyholder\'s need to pay the medical provider up front","Lowers the policy\'s premium","Converts the policy into a valued contract","Guarantees renewal of the policy"],"answer":"Reduces the policyholder\'s need to pay the medical provider up front","topic":"Right of Assignment","explanation":"Assignment lets the insurer pay the medical provider directly so the insured doesn\'t pay up front. It changes who gets the check, not the contract\'s nature."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-service","question":"When Blue Cross Blue Shield sells an HMO plan, it is acting as a:","options":["Service provider","Commercial insurer","Third-party administrator","Reinsurer"],"answer":"Service provider","topic":"Service Providers","explanation":"Service providers (like BCBS) sell benefits as SERVICES, not reimbursement. BCBS selling an HMO plan is acting as a service provider, not an insurer."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-service","question":"Service providers such as Blue Cross Blue Shield offer most benefits on what basis?","options":["A service basis rather than a reimbursement basis","A reimbursement basis rather than a service basis","A valued contract basis","A fee-for-service indemnity basis"],"answer":"A service basis rather than a reimbursement basis","topic":"Service Providers","explanation":"Service providers (like BCBS) sell benefits as SERVICES, not reimbursement. BCBS selling an HMO plan is acting as a service provider, not an insurer."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-hmo","question":"A managed care plan promotes free annual checkups, screenings, and wellness visits, aiming to catch illness early and reduce hospital admissions. This emphasis is the hallmark of:","options":["An HMO","A commercial indemnity plan","A multiple employer trust","A Medicare supplement policy"],"answer":"An HMO","topic":"HMO","explanation":"HMO = prepaid care, preventive-care emphasis, gatekeeper referrals required for specialists, no out-of-network coverage except emergencies."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-hmo","question":"Which of the following is TRUE of a health maintenance organization (HMO)?","options":["A referral from a primary care physician is needed to see a specialist","Members may see any specialist without a referral","Out-of-network care is fully covered at all times","Physicians are paid fee-for-service after each visit"],"answer":"A referral from a primary care physician is needed to see a specialist","topic":"HMO","explanation":"HMO = prepaid care, preventive-care emphasis, gatekeeper referrals required for specialists, no out-of-network coverage except emergencies."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-hmo","question":"Under an HMO plan, care received outside the network is:","options":["Not covered except in emergencies","Covered subject to a deductible and coinsurance","Covered in full after a referral","Covered at 50% of the usual charge"],"answer":"Not covered except in emergencies","topic":"HMO","explanation":"HMO = prepaid care, preventive-care emphasis, gatekeeper referrals required for specialists, no out-of-network coverage except emergencies."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-ppo","question":"Which of the following is a characteristic of a preferred provider organization (PPO)?","options":["Physicians are paid on a fee-for-service basis after the visit","Physicians are prepaid before services are rendered","A referral is required to see a specialist","Out-of-network care is never covered"],"answer":"Physicians are paid on a fee-for-service basis after the visit","topic":"PPO","explanation":"PPO = fee-for-service after the visit, no referral needed, out-of-network IS covered but acts like major medical (deductible + coinsurance)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-ppo","question":"Under a PPO, treatment received out-of-network is:","options":["Covered, functioning like major medical with a deductible and coinsurance","Not covered under any circumstances","Covered only with a gatekeeper referral","Covered in full with no cost sharing"],"answer":"Covered, functioning like major medical with a deductible and coinsurance","topic":"PPO","explanation":"PPO = fee-for-service after the visit, no referral needed, out-of-network IS covered but acts like major medical (deductible + coinsurance)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-ppo","question":"Which type of plan allows a member to see a specialist WITHOUT a referral?","options":["PPO","HMO","Medicaid managed care","A debit company plan"],"answer":"PPO","topic":"PPO","explanation":"PPO = fee-for-service after the visit, no referral needed, out-of-network IS covered but acts like major medical (deductible + coinsurance)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-pos","question":"A point-of-service (POS) plan is best described as:","options":["A hybrid that works like an HMO in-network and like a PPO out-of-network","A government program for retired workers","A self-insured arrangement administered by a TPA","A prepaid plan with no out-of-network benefits"],"answer":"A hybrid that works like an HMO in-network and like a PPO out-of-network","topic":"POS Plans","explanation":"POS = hybrid. In-network it behaves like an HMO (highest benefits); out-of-network it behaves like a PPO (claim forms, more cost-sharing)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-pos","question":"Under a POS plan, a member who receives care out-of-network:","options":["Must submit claim forms and receives PPO-like benefits","Receives no benefits whatsoever","Receives the plan\'s highest level of benefits","Pays nothing as long as the provider is licensed"],"answer":"Must submit claim forms and receives PPO-like benefits","topic":"POS Plans","explanation":"POS = hybrid. In-network it behaves like an HMO (highest benefits); out-of-network it behaves like a PPO (claim forms, more cost-sharing)."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-medicare","question":"Medicare provides coverage for which of the following groups?","options":["People 65 or older, Social Security disability income recipients, and people with chronic kidney disease","Only people 65 or older","Low-income individuals of any age","All workers injured on the job"],"answer":"People 65 or older, Social Security disability income recipients, and people with chronic kidney disease","topic":"Medicare Eligibility","explanation":"Medicare (federal): 65+, Social Security disability income recipients, and chronic kidney disease."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-medicare","question":"Medicare is administered by:","options":["The federal government","Each individual state","Private service organizations only","County health departments"],"answer":"The federal government","topic":"Medicare Eligibility","explanation":"Medicare (federal): 65+, Social Security disability income recipients, and chronic kidney disease."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-ssdi","question":"Priya became disabled in April. When will she receive her first Social Security disability benefit payment?","options":["November","September","October","December"],"answer":"November","topic":"Social Security Disability","explanation":"Must be unable to perform ANY substantial gainful work, impairment lasting 12+ months or fatal. Five-month waiting period — benefits accrue from month 6, with the first check arriving the month after. Disabled in July → first payment in February."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-ssdi","question":"Mark became disabled in March. When will he receive his first Social Security disability benefit payment?","options":["October","August","September","December"],"answer":"October","topic":"Social Security Disability","explanation":"Must be unable to perform ANY substantial gainful work, impairment lasting 12+ months or fatal. Five-month waiting period — benefits accrue from month 6, with the first check arriving the month after. Disabled in July → first payment in February."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-ssdi","question":"To qualify for Social Security disability income benefits, a person must be:","options":["Incapable of performing any substantial gainful work, with an impairment expected to last at least 12 months or result in death","Unable to perform the duties of his or her own occupation for 6 months","Over age 60 with any medically documented condition","Unemployed for at least 12 consecutive months"],"answer":"Incapable of performing any substantial gainful work, with an impairment expected to last at least 12 months or result in death","topic":"Social Security Disability","explanation":"Must be unable to perform ANY substantial gainful work, impairment lasting 12+ months or fatal. Five-month waiting period — benefits accrue from month 6, with the first check arriving the month after. Disabled in July → first payment in February."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-medicaid","question":"Darnell, 70, is wealthy but worried about future medical bills. He assumes Medicaid will cover him because of his age. Why is he mistaken?","options":["Medicaid eligibility is based on financial need, not age","Medicaid only covers people under 65","Medicaid requires 10 years of work history","Medicaid covers only children and pregnant women"],"answer":"Medicaid eligibility is based on financial need, not age","topic":"Medicaid","explanation":"Medicaid = need-based aid administered by the STATES with federal funding. No age requirement — and being blind or disabled without being poor doesn\'t qualify."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-medicaid","question":"Medicaid is administered by:","options":["The states, with federal funding","The federal government alone","Private insurers under contract","Local hospital districts"],"answer":"The states, with federal funding","topic":"Medicaid","explanation":"Medicaid = need-based aid administered by the STATES with federal funding. No age requirement — and being blind or disabled without being poor doesn\'t qualify."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-medicaid","question":"Medicaid eligibility is based primarily on:","options":["Financial need","Age 65 or older","Employment history","Prior insurance coverage"],"answer":"Financial need","topic":"Medicaid","explanation":"Medicaid = need-based aid administered by the STATES with federal funding. No age requirement — and being blind or disabled without being poor doesn\'t qualify."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-workers","question":"Which statement about workers\' compensation is TRUE?","options":["An injured worker is entitled to benefits without filing a lawsuit","Workers must sue their employer to receive benefits","Coverage is optional for most employers","It covers injuries whether or not they are work-related"],"answer":"An injured worker is entitled to benefits without filing a lawsuit","topic":"Workers\' Compensation","explanation":"Compulsory, state-mandated benefits for work-related injury/illness/death — no lawsuit required. Employers can insure, self-insure, or buy a state plan."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-workers","question":"Employers may meet their workers\' compensation obligations by:","options":["Purchasing an insurance policy, self-insuring, or purchasing a plan from the state","Only purchasing coverage from a federal program","Deducting claim costs from employee wages","Enrolling workers in an individual health plan"],"answer":"Purchasing an insurance policy, self-insuring, or purchasing a plan from the state","topic":"Workers\' Compensation","explanation":"Compulsory, state-mandated benefits for work-related injury/illness/death — no lawsuit required. Employers can insure, self-insure, or buy a state plan."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-self","question":"In a self-insured group plan that uses a third-party administrator (TPA), who retains the risk?","options":["The self-insured employer","The third-party administrator","The state insurance department","The employees"],"answer":"The self-insured employer","topic":"Self-Insurance / TPA / ASO","explanation":"A self-insured employer RETAINS all risk. TPAs and ASO arrangements only administer (claims paperwork) — they take no risk and use no actuaries."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-self","question":"An administrative-services-only (ASO) arrangement is one in which:","options":["An insurer provides administrative services, such as claims processing, to a self-insured employer","An insurer assumes full risk for an employer\'s health claims","Employees administer their own claims","The state processes claims for small employers"],"answer":"An insurer provides administrative services, such as claims processing, to a self-insured employer","topic":"Self-Insurance / TPA / ASO","explanation":"A self-insured employer RETAINS all risk. TPAs and ASO arrangements only administer (claims paperwork) — they take no risk and use no actuaries."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-self","question":"A company chooses not to buy insurance and instead sets aside its own funds to pay employee health claims directly. This company is:","options":["Self-insured","Fully insured","A service provider","A multiple employer trust"],"answer":"Self-insured","topic":"Self-Insurance / TPA / ASO","explanation":"A self-insured employer RETAINS all risk. TPAs and ASO arrangements only administer (claims paperwork) — they take no risk and use no actuaries."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-mpp","question":"A minimum premium plan (MPP) is used by self-insured businesses to:","options":["Protect against significant, unanticipated losses","Eliminate the need for a third-party administrator","Reduce employees\' share of the premium","Satisfy the ACA\'s individual mandate"],"answer":"Protect against significant, unanticipated losses","topic":"Minimum Premium Plans","explanation":"An MPP backstops a self-insured plan against large, unanticipated losses — catastrophe protection for the employer\'s own fund."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-mpp","question":"A self-insured employer wanting protection against catastrophic, unexpected claim levels would add:","options":["A minimum premium plan (MPP)","A direct primary care agreement","An optionally renewable rider","A participating dividend option"],"answer":"A minimum premium plan (MPP)","topic":"Minimum Premium Plans","explanation":"An MPP backstops a self-insured plan against large, unanticipated losses — catastrophe protection for the employer\'s own fund."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-dpc","question":"Which statement about a direct primary care agreement is TRUE?","options":["It is not insurance and does not satisfy the ACA\'s minimum coverage requirement","It qualifies as minimum essential coverage under the ACA","It indemnifies the patient for services rendered by third parties","It may be oral as long as both parties agree"],"answer":"It is not insurance and does not satisfy the ACA\'s minimum coverage requirement","topic":"Direct Primary Care","explanation":"A written agreement (signed by both physician and patient/representative) for direct payment. It is NOT insurance and does NOT satisfy ACA minimum essential coverage."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-dpc","question":"For a direct primary care agreement to be valid, it must be:","options":["In writing and signed by both the physician and the patient (or the patient\'s representative or employer)","Filed with the state insurance department","Underwritten by a licensed insurer","Approved by Medicare"],"answer":"In writing and signed by both the physician and the patient (or the patient\'s representative or employer)","topic":"Direct Primary Care","explanation":"A written agreement (signed by both physician and patient/representative) for direct payment. It is NOT insurance and does NOT satisfy ACA minimum essential coverage."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-met-mewa","question":"A multiple employer trust (MET) is best described as:","options":["Multiple employers pooling their employees through a trust that holds the master contract to obtain lower-cost coverage","A single large employer dividing employees into multiple plans","A federal program insuring small business employees","A reinsurance pool for commercial insurers"],"answer":"Multiple employers pooling their employees through a trust that holds the master contract to obtain lower-cost coverage","topic":"METs and MEWAs","explanation":"MET = employers pool employees through a trust holding the master contract. MEWA = a MET for same-industry employers with a common bond; tax-exempt. Both are state-regulated."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-met-mewa","question":"Which of the following is a requirement of a multiple employer welfare arrangement (MEWA)?","options":["Employees must share an employment-related common bond, such as being in the same industry","All member employers must have at least 500 employees","It must be administered by the federal government","Members must purchase coverage from a single commercial insurer"],"answer":"Employees must share an employment-related common bond, such as being in the same industry","topic":"METs and MEWAs","explanation":"MET = employers pool employees through a trust holding the master contract. MEWA = a MET for same-industry employers with a common bond; tax-exempt. Both are state-regulated."},{"module":"Day 3 Module 2","group":"m2-met-mewa","question":"METs and MEWAs are regulated by:","options":["The state, because they behave like insurance products","The federal government exclusively","The Securities and Exchange Commission","No regulatory body"],"answer":"The state, because they behave like insurance products","topic":"METs and MEWAs","explanation":"MET = employers pool employees through a trust holding the master contract. MEWA = a MET for same-industry employers with a common bond; tax-exempt. Both are state-regulated."},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-basicmajor","topic":"Basic vs. Major Medical","explanation":"Basic plans give first-dollar coverage with low limits; major medical gives broad, high-limit coverage with deductibles and coinsurance.","question":"A plan that pays from the first dollar but only up to low stated limits per service is a:","options":["Basic medical expense plan","Major medical plan","Comprehensive major medical plan","High-deductible health plan"],"answer":"Basic medical expense plan"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-basicmajor","topic":"Basic vs. Major Medical","explanation":"Basic plans give first-dollar coverage with low limits; major medical gives broad, high-limit coverage with deductibles and coinsurance.","question":"Which features distinguish major medical insurance from basic plans?","options":["High maximum limits with deductibles and coinsurance","First-dollar coverage with low limits","Coverage limited to surgical schedules","No cost-sharing of any kind"],"answer":"High maximum limits with deductibles and coinsurance"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-costshare","topic":"Deductibles, Coinsurance & Stop-Loss","explanation":"Cost-sharing order: deductible first, then coinsurance (e.g., 80/20), until the stop-loss limit caps the insured\'s out-of-pocket — after which the plan pays 100%.","question":"After Roy meets his deductible, his plan pays 80% of covered charges until his out-of-pocket reaches $6,000, after which it pays 100%. The $6,000 figure is the:","options":["Stop-loss limit","Coinsurance percentage","Carryover deductible","UCR limit"],"answer":"Stop-loss limit"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-costshare","topic":"Deductibles, Coinsurance & Stop-Loss","explanation":"Cost-sharing order: deductible first, then coinsurance (e.g., 80/20), until the stop-loss limit caps the insured\'s out-of-pocket — after which the plan pays 100%.","question":"Three members of the Diaz family are injured in the same car crash. Their plan applies only one deductible for all three claims. This reflects a:","options":["Common accident provision","Carryover provision","Family stop-loss provision","Coordination of benefits provision"],"answer":"Common accident provision"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-carryover","topic":"Carryover Deductible","explanation":"A carryover provision lets expenses incurred in the last three months of the year count toward NEXT year\'s deductible.","question":"Expenses Quinn incurred in November and December that didn\'t satisfy this year\'s deductible may count toward next year\'s deductible under a:","options":["Carryover provision","Common accident provision","Stop-loss provision","Probationary provision"],"answer":"Carryover provision"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-carryover","topic":"Carryover Deductible","explanation":"A carryover provision lets expenses incurred in the last three months of the year count toward NEXT year\'s deductible.","question":"The carryover deductible provision applies to expenses incurred during:","options":["The last three months of the calendar year","The first 31 days of coverage","Any month premiums were waived","The elimination period"],"answer":"The last three months of the calendar year"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-hsa","topic":"HSA Eligibility","explanation":"HSAs require a high-deductible health plan (HDHP), no other first-dollar coverage, no Medicare enrollment, and not being claimed as a dependent. Contributions, growth, and qualified withdrawals are all tax-advantaged, and funds roll over.","question":"To be eligible to contribute to a Health Savings Account, a person must:","options":["Be covered by a high-deductible health plan","Be enrolled in Medicare Part A","Have a flexible spending account","Earn less than 400% of the poverty level"],"answer":"Be covered by a high-deductible health plan"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-hsa","topic":"HSA Eligibility","explanation":"HSAs require a high-deductible health plan (HDHP), no other first-dollar coverage, no Medicare enrollment, and not being claimed as a dependent. Contributions, growth, and qualified withdrawals are all tax-advantaged, and funds roll over.","question":"Which statement about Health Savings Accounts is TRUE?","options":["Unused funds roll over from year to year and belong to the account holder","Unused funds are forfeited each December 31","Only employers may contribute","Withdrawals for medical care are taxed as income"],"answer":"Unused funds roll over from year to year and belong to the account holder"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-fsa-hra","topic":"FSA vs. HRA","explanation":"FSA = employee-funded pre-tax, use-it-or-lose-it. HRA = employer-funded only, reimburses medical expenses, rollover at employer\'s discretion.","question":"Which account is funded ONLY by the employer?","options":["Health Reimbursement Arrangement (HRA)","Health Savings Account (HSA)","Flexible Spending Account (FSA)","Individual retirement account"],"answer":"Health Reimbursement Arrangement (HRA)"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-fsa-hra","topic":"FSA vs. HRA","explanation":"FSA = employee-funded pre-tax, use-it-or-lose-it. HRA = employer-funded only, reimburses medical expenses, rollover at employer\'s discretion.","question":"The \'use it or lose it\' rule is most associated with:","options":["Flexible Spending Accounts","Health Savings Accounts","Health Reimbursement Arrangements","High-deductible health plans"],"answer":"Flexible Spending Accounts"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-ucr","topic":"Usual, Customary & Reasonable","explanation":"UCR-based plans pay what providers in the geographic area typically charge; amounts billed above UCR are the insured\'s responsibility.","question":"Dr. Patel bills $500 for a procedure, but the plan\'s usual, customary and reasonable amount is $400. The insured is responsible for:","options":["The $100 above the UCR amount, plus any normal cost-sharing","Nothing — UCR protects the insured fully","The entire $500","Only the copayment"],"answer":"The $100 above the UCR amount, plus any normal cost-sharing"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-ucr","topic":"Usual, Customary & Reasonable","explanation":"UCR-based plans pay what providers in the geographic area typically charge; amounts billed above UCR are the insured\'s responsibility.","question":"\'Usual, customary and reasonable\' charges are based on:","options":["What providers in the same geographic area typically charge for the service","The insurer\'s home-office fee schedule","Medicare\'s national rates","The provider\'s costs plus 20%"],"answer":"What providers in the same geographic area typically charge for the service"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-dental","topic":"Dental Plan Tiers","explanation":"Dental coverage tiers: preventive/diagnostic ~100%, basic (fillings) ~80%, major (crowns, dentures) ~50% — often with waiting periods and annual maximums.","question":"Which dental services are typically covered at the HIGHEST percentage?","options":["Preventive and diagnostic services like cleanings and exams","Crowns and bridges","Dentures","Orthodontics"],"answer":"Preventive and diagnostic services like cleanings and exams"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-dental","topic":"Dental Plan Tiers","explanation":"Dental coverage tiers: preventive/diagnostic ~100%, basic (fillings) ~80%, major (crowns, dentures) ~50% — often with waiting periods and annual maximums.","question":"Compared with medical insurance, dental plans commonly include:","options":["Calendar-year maximums and waiting periods for major services","Unlimited lifetime benefits","No cost-sharing","Coverage only after hospitalization"],"answer":"Calendar-year maximums and waiting periods for major services"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-firstdollar","topic":"First Dollar Insurance","explanation":"Basic medical expense plans pay from the first dollar — no deductible. They control costs through benefit LIMITS instead, which is also why their premiums are least affected by rising medical costs... that distinction belongs to hospital indemnity. First dollar = basic plans.","question":"Which type of policy pays benefits up front, without a deductible, and is known as \'first dollar\' insurance?","options":["A basic medical expense policy","A major medical policy","A disability income policy","A business overhead expense policy"],"answer":"A basic medical expense policy"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-firstdollar","topic":"First Dollar Insurance","explanation":"Basic medical expense plans pay from the first dollar — no deductible. They control costs through benefit LIMITS instead.","question":"Basic medical plans avoid small claims and keep premiums down by:","options":["Imposing benefit limits","Using deductibles and coinsurance","Paying only catastrophic expenses","Restricting members to network physicians"],"answer":"Imposing benefit limits"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-misc","topic":"Miscellaneous Expense Benefit","explanation":"The basic hospital miscellaneous benefit covers hospital \'extras\': drugs, X-rays, anesthesia, lab fees, dressings, operating room, supplies. It does NOT cover room and board or physicians\' bedside visits, and its limit is often a multiple of the daily room-and-board benefit.","question":"The miscellaneous expense benefit in a basic hospital expense policy normally covers:","options":["Drugs and medicine administered in the hospital","Physicians\' bedside visits","Hospital room and board","The surgeon\'s professional fee"],"answer":"Drugs and medicine administered in the hospital"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-misc","topic":"Miscellaneous Expense Benefit","explanation":"The basic hospital miscellaneous benefit covers hospital \'extras\': drugs, X-rays, anesthesia, lab fees, dressings, operating room, supplies. It does NOT cover room and board or physicians\' bedside visits, and its limit is often a multiple of the daily room-and-board benefit.","question":"In a basic hospital expense policy, the limit for miscellaneous expenses is typically expressed as a multiple of the:","options":["Daily room and board benefit","Surgeon\'s scheduled fee","Annual deductible","Stop-loss limit"],"answer":"Daily room and board benefit"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-misc","topic":"Miscellaneous Expense Benefit","explanation":"The basic hospital miscellaneous benefit covers hospital \'extras\': drugs, X-rays, anesthesia, lab fees, dressings, operating room, supplies. It does NOT cover room and board or physicians\' bedside visits.","question":"Which of the following is NOT covered by the basic hospital expense policy\'s miscellaneous benefit?","options":["Physicians\' bedside visits","Use of the operating room","Anesthesia","Drugs and dressings"],"answer":"Physicians\' bedside visits"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-misc","topic":"Miscellaneous Expense Benefit","explanation":"Memorize the trio: anesthesia (the drug/substance) → covered as miscellaneous; the anesthesiologist (the physician administering it) → NOT covered — that\'s a physician\'s professional fee; physicians\' bedside visits → NOT covered. Watch the wording: \'anesthesia\' is right, \'the administering of anesthesia\' is the trap.","question":"Under a basic hospital expense policy\'s miscellaneous benefit, which of the following is NOT covered?","options":["The anesthesiologist\'s professional services","Anesthesia","X-rays and lab fees","Use of the operating room"],"answer":"The anesthesiologist\'s professional services"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-surgmethods","topic":"Surgical Payment Methods","explanation":"Three methods: surgical schedule (flat dollar value per procedure), reasonable & customary (regional comparison — excess is the patient\'s), relative value scale (points × conversion factor).","question":"Pavel\'s basic surgical policy assigns 60 points to an appendectomy and uses a $10 conversion factor. How much will the policy pay?","options":["$600","$500","$540","$700"],"answer":"$600"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-surgmethods","topic":"Surgical Payment Methods","explanation":"Three methods: surgical schedule (flat dollar value per procedure), reasonable & customary (regional comparison — excess is the patient\'s), relative value scale (points × conversion factor).","question":"Which basic surgical plan assigns a system of POINTS to surgical procedures?","options":["Relative value scale","Surgical schedule","Reasonable and customary","Stated charges"],"answer":"Relative value scale"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-surgmethods","topic":"Surgical Payment Methods","explanation":"Three methods: surgical schedule (flat dollar value), reasonable & customary (compares the charge to the typical cost in that geographic region), relative value scale (points × conversion factor).","question":"Determining the cost of a surgical procedure by comparing it to typical charges in the same geographic area describes the:","options":["Reasonable and customary approach","Surgical schedule method","Relative value scale","Conversion factor method"],"answer":"Reasonable and customary approach"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-fixedrate","topic":"Hospital Indemnity / Fixed-Rate Plans","explanation":"Fixed-rate (hospital indemnity) plans pay a flat daily/weekly/monthly amount per day hospitalized, directly TO THE INSURED. Fixed benefits mean claim costs aren\'t affected by medical inflation — and the premium is least affected by rising medical costs. BANK QUIRK: one bank question asks what \'basis\' a flat-per-day policy pays on and keys \'reimbursement\' even with \'fixed-rate plan\' as an option; another keys \'fixed-rate.\' Read the options: if the question describes WHAT it pays, answer flat amount per day / fixed-rate; if it asks the payment \'basis\' with reimbursement keyed, the bank uses the terms interchangeably.","question":"A hospital expense policy that pays a flat amount per day of hospitalization pays benefits on what basis?","options":["A fixed-rate plan","Reimbursement","Service","Assignment"],"answer":"A fixed-rate plan"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-fixedrate","topic":"Hospital Indemnity / Fixed-Rate Plans","explanation":"Fixed-rate (hospital indemnity) plans pay a flat daily amount per day hospitalized, directly TO THE INSURED — not to the hospital.","question":"Which statement about a hospital fixed-rate (indemnity) plan is NOT true?","options":["Benefits are paid directly to the hospital","Claim costs are not affected by rising healthcare costs","It offers high benefits for relatively low premiums","Underwriting and administration are simple"],"answer":"Benefits are paid directly to the hospital"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-fixedrate","topic":"Hospital Indemnity / Fixed-Rate Plans","explanation":"Because its benefit is a fixed dollar amount per day rather than a share of actual charges, hospital indemnity premiums are the least affected by rising medical costs.","question":"Which coverage\'s premium is LEAST affected by an increase in medical costs?","options":["Hospital indemnity","Major medical","Comprehensive medical","Basic medical expense"],"answer":"Hospital indemnity"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-dedtypes","topic":"Major Medical Deductible Types","explanation":"Three major medical deductibles: flat (fixed sum), corridor (insured pays the full deductible after BASIC benefits are exhausted), integrated (the deductible can be offset by what the basic plan pays). Stop-loss is NOT a deductible.","question":"Which of the following is NOT one of the three types of major medical deductibles?","options":["Stop-loss","Corridor","Integrated","Flat"],"answer":"Stop-loss"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-dedtypes","topic":"Major Medical Deductible Types","explanation":"Corridor: basic plan pays first, then the insured pays the full deductible before major medical kicks in. Integrated: basic plan payments can satisfy (offset) the deductible. Flat: a simple fixed sum.","question":"Hana\'s basic plan paid $2,400 of her hospital bill. She then paid a $200 deductible before her major medical coverage began paying. Her deductible is classified as:","options":["Corridor","Integrated","Flat","Split"],"answer":"Corridor"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-dedtypes","topic":"Major Medical Deductible Types","explanation":"Corridor: insured pays the full deductible after basic benefits are exhausted. Integrated: amounts the basic plan pays offset (satisfy) the deductible.","question":"If all or part of a $500 major medical deductible can be satisfied by benefits paid under a basic medical policy, the deductible is:","options":["Integrated","Corridor","Flat","Carryover"],"answer":"Integrated"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-majormath","topic":"Major Medical Math","explanation":"Deductible first, then coinsurance on what remains: insured pays deductible + their percentage of the balance, up to any stop-loss.","question":"Vera\'s hospital bill is $10,500. Her major medical policy has a $500 deductible and 80/20 coinsurance. How much does Vera pay in total?","options":["$2,500","$2,000","$500","$2,100"],"answer":"$2,500"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-majormath","topic":"Major Medical Math","explanation":"Deductible first, then coinsurance on what remains: insured pays deductible + their percentage of the balance.","question":"Andre\'s covered expenses total $8,000. His policy has a $500 flat deductible and an 80/20 coinsurance provision. The INSURER pays:","options":["$6,000","$7,500","$6,400","$5,500"],"answer":"$6,000"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-basicmath","topic":"Basic Plan Benefit Limits","explanation":"Basic plans pay each category only up to its stated limit: daily room-and-board rate × days (regardless of actual charges), the scheduled surgical amount, and miscellaneous up to its cap.","question":"Talia\'s basic hospital/surgical policy pays $60/day room and board, schedules her surgery at $400, and caps miscellaneous charges at $500. She is hospitalized 5 days at $90/day, billed $550 for surgery and $620 miscellaneous. The policy pays:","options":["$1,200","$1,470","$1,770","$900"],"answer":"$1,200"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-basicmath","topic":"Basic Plan Benefit Limits","explanation":"Basic plans pay each category only up to its stated limit: daily room-and-board rate × days, the scheduled surgical amount, and miscellaneous up to its cap. Amounts billed above each limit are the insured\'s responsibility.","question":"Under a schedule-approach basic policy, the surgeon bills $675 but the procedure is scheduled at $500. The policy pays:","options":["$500 — the scheduled amount","$675 — the billed amount","$587.50 — the average","Nothing until the deductible is met"],"answer":"$500 — the scheduled amount"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-limited","topic":"Limited Risk Policies","explanation":"Limited risk policies cover one specific peril or ailment: dread disease/cancer policies, travel accident, hospital indemnity, accident-only. They pay limited amounts for narrow risks.","question":"Dread disease, travel accident, and hospital indemnity policies are all examples of:","options":["Limited risk policies","Comprehensive major medical","Blanket policies","Basic physicians\' expense plans"],"answer":"Limited risk policies"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-limited","topic":"Limited Risk Policies","explanation":"A limited risk (dread disease) policy protects against one named ailment — cancer is the classic example.","question":"A limited risk policy pays benefits for dread diseases:","options":["Such as cancer","Only if terminal","Only if chronic","Of any kind, like major medical"],"answer":"Such as cancer"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-shortterm","topic":"Short-Term Medical (Florida)","explanation":"Florida defines short-term medical insurance as coverage expiring less than 12 months after its effective date, not exceeding 36 months including renewals.","question":"Under Florida\'s definition, a short-term medical policy must expire less than ______ after its effective date and cannot exceed ______ in total duration.","options":["12 months; 36 months","6 months; 12 months","12 months; 24 months","24 months; 48 months"],"answer":"12 months; 36 months"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-shortterm","topic":"Short-Term Medical (Florida)","explanation":"Short-term medical policies cover a specific limited period (e.g., 90 or 180 days); accident-only policies cover accidents but never illness.","question":"A policy that covers injuries from accidents but provides NO coverage for sickness is:","options":["Accident-only insurance","Short-term major medical","A dread disease policy","Comprehensive coverage"],"answer":"Accident-only insurance"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-suppcomp","topic":"Supplementary vs. Comprehensive","explanation":"Supplementary major medical layers on top of a basic plan, covering excluded expenses and amounts beyond the basic plan\'s limits. Comprehensive combines basic + major medical in one policy.","question":"A major medical plan that covers expenses a basic plan excludes — plus expenses exceeding the basic plan\'s limits — is a:","options":["Supplementary major medical plan","Comprehensive major medical plan","Hospital indemnity plan","Limited risk plan"],"answer":"Supplementary major medical plan"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-suppcomp","topic":"Supplementary vs. Comprehensive","explanation":"A supplementary major medical plan combines with BASIC medical coverage; a comprehensive plan covers nearly everything in one policy with a deductible and coinsurance.","question":"A supplementary major medical policy combines the benefits of which two plan types?","options":["Basic medical and major medical","Hospital expense and surgical expense","Major medical and disability income","AD&D and major medical"],"answer":"Basic medical and major medical"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-dedpurpose","topic":"Why Deductibles Exist","explanation":"Deductibles eliminate small claims and hold premiums down by making the insured pay initial expenses. They are common in MAJOR MEDICAL plans — basic plans are first-dollar coverage.","question":"Which statement about deductibles in medical insurance is NOT correct?","options":["They are most common in basic medical expense policies","They help eliminate small claims","They make the insured pay initial expenses up to a set amount","They help hold premium rates down"],"answer":"They are most common in basic medical expense policies"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-dedpurpose","topic":"Why Deductibles Exist","explanation":"Deductibles eliminate small claims; coinsurance discourages overutilization of benefits. Together they\'re the two main cost-sharing components of major medical.","question":"Which of the following is TRUE about coinsurance?","options":["It helps control overutilization of benefits","It applies to the deductible as well as claim payments","Premiums are higher with a coinsurance provision than without","The insurer can change the ratio after issue"],"answer":"It helps control overutilization of benefits"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-lostincome","topic":"What Medical Plans Don\'t Cover","explanation":"Medical expense insurance pays care costs — it never replaces lost income. Income replacement is disability income insurance\'s job.","question":"Basic medical expense policies generally provide NO coverage for:","options":["Lost income","Emergency room visits","Surgical expenses","Skilled nursing facility expenses"],"answer":"Lost income"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-lostincome","topic":"What Medical Plans Don\'t Cover","explanation":"Higher risks and greater potential losses call for major medical — broad coverage with high limits — not first-dollar basic plans or single-disease policies.","question":"Which medical expense plan is best suited for higher risks and greater potential loss?","options":["Major medical","First dollar (basic) coverage","A cancer policy","AD&D"],"answer":"Major medical"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-preexist","topic":"Preexisting Conditions","explanation":"A preexisting condition existed before the policy\'s effective date. Exclusion periods protected insurers from adverse selection — but the ACA eliminated preexisting-condition exclusions in ACA-compliant medical plans.","question":"Historically, preexisting-condition exclusion periods protected insurers against:","options":["Adverse selection","Catastrophic claims","Premium inflation","Overutilization of benefits"],"answer":"Adverse selection"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 1","group":"mp-preexist","topic":"Preexisting Conditions","explanation":"A preexisting condition existed before the policy\'s effective date. The ACA eliminated preexisting-condition exclusions in ACA-compliant medical expense plans.","question":"Under the Affordable Care Act, preexisting condition exclusions in compliant major medical plans are:","options":["Prohibited entirely","Limited to 12 months","Allowed for chronic illness only","Allowed with a premium surcharge"],"answer":"Prohibited entirely"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-elim","topic":"Elimination vs. Probationary","explanation":"The elimination period is the \'time deductible\' before benefits start (longer = cheaper premium). Per this course\'s bank it applies to SICKNESS only — accidents are payable immediately. The probationary period applies once, at policy start, to sickness only.","question":"The waiting period between the onset of a disability and the start of benefit payments is the:","options":["Elimination period","Probationary period","Grace period","Benefit period"],"answer":"Elimination period"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-elim","topic":"Elimination vs. Probationary","explanation":"The elimination period is the \'time deductible\' before benefits start (longer = cheaper premium). Per this course\'s bank it applies to SICKNESS only — accidents are payable immediately. The probationary period applies once, at policy start, to sickness only.","question":"Choosing a 180-day elimination period instead of 30 days will:","options":["Lower the premium","Raise the premium","Shorten the benefit period","Eliminate the probationary period"],"answer":"Lower the premium"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-prob","topic":"Probationary Period","explanation":"The probationary period is a one-time window at the start of the policy during which sickness (never accidents) is not covered — it blocks preexisting-illness claims.","question":"A disability policy\'s probationary period applies to:","options":["Sickness only, during the period right after the policy is issued","Accidents only","Both sickness and accidents, on every claim","Claims filed after age 65"],"answer":"Sickness only, during the period right after the policy is issued"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-prob","topic":"Probationary Period","explanation":"The probationary period is a one-time window at the start of the policy during which sickness (never accidents) is not covered — it blocks preexisting-illness claims.","question":"Two weeks after buying a disability policy with a 30-day probationary period, Lena is hurt in a car accident and cannot work. The insurer will:","options":["Pay — the probationary period does not apply to accidents","Deny — no claims are covered during the probationary period","Pay only half the benefit","Refund her premium and void the policy"],"answer":"Pay — the probationary period does not apply to accidents"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-occ","topic":"Own vs. Any Occupation","explanation":"Own-occupation pays if you can\'t do YOUR job (easier to qualify, costlier). Any-occupation pays only if you can\'t do any job suited to your education, training, or experience.","question":"Under an own-occupation definition of disability, a surgeon who loses fine motor control but takes a teaching job will:","options":["Receive benefits, because she cannot perform her own occupation","Receive nothing, because she can still work","Receive benefits only after age 65","Forfeit the policy"],"answer":"Receive benefits, because she cannot perform her own occupation"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-occ","topic":"Own vs. Any Occupation","explanation":"Counterintuitive but course-keyed: under the own-occupation definition, a PERMANENT inability to perform your own regular occupation is PERMANENT TOTAL disability — even if you can do other work. \'Partial\' means you can still perform SOME duties of your own occupation, not that you can do a different job.","question":"A worker is permanently unable to perform the duties of his own regular occupation, but is capable of working in a different field. Under the own-occupation definition, his disability is classified as:","options":["Permanent total disability","Permanent partial disability","Temporary total disability","Residual disability"],"answer":"Permanent total disability"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-occ","topic":"Own vs. Any Occupation","explanation":"Own-occupation pays if you can\'t do YOUR job (easier to qualify, costlier). Any-occupation pays only if you can\'t do any job suited to your education, training, or experience.","question":"Which definition of total disability is most favorable to the insured?","options":["Own occupation","Any occupation","Presumptive occupation","Residual occupation"],"answer":"Own occupation"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-residual","topic":"Partial vs. Residual","explanation":"Partial disability pays a flat percentage (often 50%) of the total benefit. Residual pays in proportion to lost INCOME — a 40% earnings drop pays 40% of the benefit.","question":"Marco returned to work part-time and his earnings dropped 40%. His policy pays 40% of his total disability benefit. This is a ______ benefit.","options":["Residual disability","Partial disability","Presumptive disability","Recurrent disability"],"answer":"Residual disability"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-residual","topic":"Partial vs. Residual","explanation":"Partial disability pays a flat percentage (often 50%) of the total benefit. Residual pays in proportion to lost INCOME — a 40% earnings drop pays 40% of the benefit.","question":"A benefit that pays a flat 50% of the total disability benefit when the insured can work but cannot perform all duties is:","options":["Partial disability","Residual disability","Total disability","Presumptive disability"],"answer":"Partial disability"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-presume","topic":"Presumptive Disability","explanation":"Presumptive disability automatically qualifies as total disability without further proof: loss of sight, hearing, speech, or two limbs.","question":"Which loss would trigger a presumptive total disability benefit?","options":["Loss of sight in both eyes","A sprained ankle","A 20% loss of income","Carpal tunnel syndrome"],"answer":"Loss of sight in both eyes"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-presume","topic":"Presumptive Disability","explanation":"Presumptive disability automatically qualifies as total disability without further proof: loss of sight, hearing, speech, or two limbs.","question":"Under a presumptive disability provision, the insured who loses two limbs:","options":["Is automatically considered totally disabled, with no further proof required","Must still prove she cannot perform her occupation","Receives only partial benefits","Must satisfy a new probationary period"],"answer":"Is automatically considered totally disabled, with no further proof required"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-boe","topic":"Business Overhead Expense","explanation":"BOE pays the business\'s operating expenses (rent, utilities, staff salaries) while the owner is disabled. It does NOT replace the owner\'s income.","question":"Tariq owns a dental practice. He wants coverage that pays the office rent and his hygienist\'s salary if he becomes disabled. He needs:","options":["Business overhead expense insurance","Personal disability income insurance","Key person life insurance","A disability buy-sell agreement"],"answer":"Business overhead expense insurance"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-boe","topic":"Business Overhead Expense","explanation":"BOE pays the business\'s operating expenses (rent, utilities, staff salaries) while the owner is disabled. It does NOT replace the owner\'s income.","question":"Business overhead expense insurance does NOT cover:","options":["The disabled owner\'s lost personal income","Office rent","Employee salaries","Utility bills"],"answer":"The disabled owner\'s lost personal income"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-buysell","topic":"Disability Buy-Sell","explanation":"A disability buy-sell funds the purchase of a disabled partner\'s interest in the business, usually as a lump sum after a long elimination period.","question":"A policy designed to fund the purchase of a totally disabled partner\'s share of the business is a:","options":["Disability buy-sell policy","Business overhead expense policy","Key person retention policy","Group disability conversion"],"answer":"Disability buy-sell policy"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-buysell","topic":"Disability Buy-Sell","explanation":"A disability buy-sell funds the purchase of a disabled partner\'s interest in the business, usually as a lump sum after a long elimination period.","question":"Compared to personal disability income policies, disability buy-sell policies typically have:","options":["A longer elimination period and a lump-sum benefit","A shorter elimination period and monthly benefits","No elimination period","Benefits payable to the disabled partner\'s family"],"answer":"A longer elimination period and a lump-sum benefit"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-waiver","topic":"Waiver of Premium","explanation":"Waiver of premium keeps the policy in force without payments while the insured is totally disabled, typically kicking in after 90 days and refunding premiums paid during that time.","question":"The provision that keeps a disability policy in force without premium payments while the insured is totally disabled is:","options":["Waiver of premium","Grace period","Reinstatement","Automatic premium loan"],"answer":"Waiver of premium"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-waiver","topic":"Waiver of Premium","explanation":"Waiver of premium keeps the policy in force without payments while the insured is totally disabled, typically kicking in after 90 days and refunding premiums paid during that time.","question":"The Social Insurance Supplement (SIS) rider pays:","options":["An extra benefit while the insured awaits or is denied Social Security disability benefits","The insured\'s Social Security taxes","A funeral benefit","The employer\'s share of FICA"],"answer":"An extra benefit while the insured awaits or is denied Social Security disability benefits"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-cause","topic":"Accidental Means vs. Bodily Injury","explanation":"Accidental means requires the CAUSE itself to be unintended — a deliberate act (like jumping into a lake) that produces an unintended injury is NOT covered. Accidental bodily injury only requires the RESULT to be unexpected, so it\'s broader.","question":"Mateo\'s disability policy uses an \'accidental means\' definition. He deliberately jumped from a dock into shallow water and broke his neck. The insurer will:","options":["Pay nothing — the jump was intentional, so the cause was not accidental","Pay in full — the injury was not planned","Pay half the benefit","Pay only medical expenses"],"answer":"Pay nothing — the jump was intentional, so the cause was not accidental"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-cause","topic":"Accidental Means vs. Bodily Injury","explanation":"Accidental means requires the CAUSE itself to be unintended. Accidental bodily injury only requires the RESULT to be unexpected, so it\'s the broader, more favorable definition.","question":"Which definition of accident requires that BOTH the cause and the result be unexpected and unintended?","options":["Accidental means","Accidental bodily injury","Presumptive cause","Proximate cause"],"answer":"Accidental means"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-cause","topic":"Accidental Means vs. Bodily Injury","explanation":"Under accidental bodily injury, only the result must be accidental — a hiker who accidentally falls is covered. Under accidental means, a deliberate act that goes wrong is not covered.","question":"While hiking, Joelle accidentally slips off a trail ledge and is paralyzed. Under an \'accidental bodily injury\' provision, her claim is:","options":["Covered — the injury was unexpected and accidental","Denied — hiking is a voluntary activity","Covered at 50%","Denied — falls are excluded"],"answer":"Covered — the injury was unexpected and accidental"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-delayed","topic":"Delayed Disability","explanation":"The delayed disability provision covers a disability that develops after an accident — up to a maximum of 90 days following the accident.","question":"Under a delayed disability provision, a disability that develops after an accident is still covered if it begins within a maximum of:","options":["90 days of the accident","30 days of the accident","6 months of the accident","1 year of the accident"],"answer":"90 days of the accident"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-delayed","topic":"Delayed Disability","explanation":"The delayed disability provision covers a disability that develops after an accident — up to a maximum of 90 days following the accident.","question":"Caleb is in a car crash in May but doesn\'t become disabled from his injuries until July (within 90 days). Which provision allows his claim?","options":["The delayed disability provision","The recurrent disability provision","The probationary period","The elective indemnity option"],"answer":"The delayed disability provision"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-nondis","topic":"Non-Disabling Injury Benefit","explanation":"A non-disabling injury doesn\'t keep the insured from working — the benefit pays the ACTUAL COST of medical treatment for the injury, never a salary percentage.","question":"An injury that does not qualify the insured for monthly disability benefits may still make him eligible for:","options":["A non-disabling injury benefit","An emergency room benefit","Outpatient compensation","A presumptive benefit"],"answer":"A non-disabling injury benefit"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-nondis","topic":"Non-Disabling Injury Benefit","explanation":"A non-disabling injury benefit pays the actual cost of medical treatment for an accidental injury that doesn\'t prevent the insured from working.","question":"The non-disabling injury benefit pays:","options":["The actual cost of medical treatment","A flat amount equal to the insured\'s salary","A percentage of the insured\'s salary","The full monthly disability benefit"],"answer":"The actual cost of medical treatment"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-elective","topic":"Elective Indemnity","explanation":"Elective indemnity, available on some short-term disability policies, lets the insured choose a lump-sum payment for certain named injuries instead of income payments.","question":"An option on some short-term disability policies allowing the insured to take a LUMP SUM for certain named injuries is called:","options":["Elective indemnity","Residual indemnity","Double indemnity","Presumptive indemnity"],"answer":"Elective indemnity"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-elective","topic":"Elective Indemnity","explanation":"Elective indemnity, available on some short-term disability policies, lets the insured choose a lump-sum payment for certain named injuries instead of weekly or monthly income.","question":"Instead of receiving monthly income for his fractured arm, Drew elects a one-time lump-sum payment named in his short-term policy. He has exercised:","options":["An elective indemnity option","A waiver of premium","A COLA adjustment","A Social Security rider"],"answer":"An elective indemnity option"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-benper","topic":"Benefit Periods & Premium Cost","explanation":"Short-term individual DI benefit periods run six months to two years. Premium cost rises with longer benefit periods and falls with longer elimination periods — so long elimination + short benefit period is cheapest.","question":"Individual short-term disability policy benefit periods typically range from:","options":["Six months to two years","One to 12 months","Three months to three years","One to five years"],"answer":"Six months to two years"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-benper","topic":"Benefit Periods & Premium Cost","explanation":"Premium cost rises with longer benefit periods and falls with longer elimination periods — long elimination + short benefit period is the cheapest combination.","question":"Which disability policy configuration carries the LOWEST premium?","options":["A long elimination period with a short benefit period","A short elimination period with a long benefit period","A long elimination period with a long benefit period","A short elimination period with a short benefit period"],"answer":"A long elimination period with a short benefit period"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-benper","topic":"Benefit Periods & Premium Cost","explanation":"A benefit period \'to age 65\' ends at 65 no matter when disability begins. Disabled at 64½ with a 6-month waiting period, the insured reaches 65 just as the wait ends — nothing is payable.","question":"Imelda has a $1,500/month disability policy with benefits to age 65 and a six-month waiting period. She becomes disabled at age 64½. She will receive:","options":["Nothing — the benefit period ends at 65, just as her waiting period is satisfied","$1,500 for one month","$9,000","$18,000"],"answer":"Nothing — the benefit period ends at 65, just as her waiting period is satisfied"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-payment","topic":"Payment of Benefits","explanation":"Individual disability income claims must be paid no less frequently than monthly.","question":"At a minimum, disability income claim payments must be made to the insured:","options":["Monthly","Weekly","Quarterly","Annually"],"answer":"Monthly"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-payment","topic":"Payment of Benefits","explanation":"Disability benefits are paid as periodic income — monthly at minimum — not as lump sums (except under elective indemnity options).","question":"Disability income benefits are typically paid:","options":["Monthly","Quarterly","Semiannually","In a single lump sum"],"answer":"Monthly"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-occnon","topic":"Occupational vs. Nonoccupational","explanation":"Occupational coverage protects on AND off the job. Nonoccupational covers only off-the-job disabilities — on-the-job injuries fall to workers\' compensation.","question":"A nonoccupational disability policy covers:","options":["Only disabilities occurring OFF the job","Only disabilities occurring on the job","All disabilities, on or off the job","Only occupational diseases"],"answer":"Only disabilities occurring OFF the job"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-occnon","topic":"Occupational vs. Nonoccupational","explanation":"Occupational coverage protects on AND off the job. Nonoccupational covers only off-the-job disabilities — on-the-job injuries fall to workers\' compensation.","question":"Why are most group disability plans written as NONoccupational coverage?","options":["On-the-job injuries are already covered by workers\' compensation","Off-the-job injuries are rarer","Federal law prohibits occupational coverage","Premiums are higher for nonoccupational plans"],"answer":"On-the-job injuries are already covered by workers\' compensation"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-recur","topic":"Recurrent Disability","explanation":"If the same disability returns within the stated window (commonly 6 months), benefits resume immediately — no new elimination period. But beware the course\'s flip side: full recovery + return to work can make a later disability a NEW claim with a new elimination period (see the Marcus question).","question":"Rosa was disabled January 15 to April 15, returned to work, then was stricken by the same condition on September 1. Under the recurrent disability provision, her benefits:","options":["Resume September 1, with no new elimination period","Begin after a brand-new elimination period","Begin after a new probationary period","Are denied as a preexisting condition"],"answer":"Resume September 1, with no new elimination period"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-recur","topic":"Recurrent Disability","explanation":"A recurrence within the stated window continues the original claim. A NEW, separate disability starts a new elimination period and a fresh benefit period.","question":"The purpose of the recurrent disability provision is to:","options":["Treat a relapse within a stated period as a continuation of the original claim, with no new elimination period","Reduce benefits for repeat claims","Extend the probationary period after each claim","Convert the policy to medical expense coverage"],"answer":"Treat a relapse within a stated period as a continuation of the original claim, with no new elimination period"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-recur","topic":"Recurrent Disability","explanation":"Course-keyed distinction: a relapse within the recurrence window continues the original claim (no new elimination period). But FULL recovery plus a return to work means a later disability — even from the same cause — is treated as a NEW disability: a new elimination period applies and a fresh benefit period begins.","question":"Marcus was disabled by a stroke, fully recovered, and returned to work for three months before a second stroke disabled him on June 1. His policy has a 30-day elimination period and a 5-year benefit period. The insurer will:","options":["Begin benefits July 1 and pay up to a fresh 5-year benefit period","Resume benefits June 1 under the recurrent disability provision","Pay only the remainder of the original benefit period","Deny the claim as a preexisting condition"],"answer":"Begin benefits July 1 and pay up to a fresh 5-year benefit period"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-totaldef","topic":"Occupational Suitability","explanation":"Any-occupation tests look at education, training, and experience. Job interest is never a criterion. House confinement and inability to perform own/any occupation have been used in definitions of total disability.","question":"Which of the following is NOT a criterion used to assess total disability based on occupational suitability?","options":["Job interest","Education","Training","Experience"],"answer":"Job interest"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-totaldef","topic":"Occupational Suitability","explanation":"\'Any occupation for which the insured is qualified by education or experience\' is the ANY-occupation definition — the more restrictive one (hardest to qualify under). Own-occupation is less restrictive and more favorable. WARNING: this course\'s bank has keyed this BOTH ways (\'more restrictive\' and \'less restrictive\'). Standard/state-exam answer: any-occupation = MORE restrictive. Flag the contradiction to your instructor if marked wrong.","question":"A policy defines total disability as the inability to perform ANY occupation for which the insured is qualified by education or experience. This definition is:","options":["The any-occupation definition, and it is more restrictive than own-occupation","The own-occupation definition, and it is more restrictive","The any-occupation definition, and it is less restrictive","The own-occupation definition, and it is less restrictive"],"answer":"The any-occupation definition, and it is more restrictive than own-occupation"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-elimscenario","topic":"Elimination Period Scenarios","explanation":"Benefits never accrue during the elimination period and are NOT retroactive. If the insured recovers before the elimination period ends, nothing is paid.","question":"Jonas has a 30-day elimination period. He is sick and out of work for 15 days, then returns. His disability benefit is paid:","options":["Never — he recovered before satisfying the elimination period","Beginning on day 1, retroactively","Beginning on day 16","Beginning on day 31"],"answer":"Never — he recovered before satisfying the elimination period"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-elimscenario","topic":"Elimination Period Scenarios","explanation":"Statements that elimination benefits are paid retroactively, or that elimination periods apply to sickness but not accidents, are FALSE — that second description fits the probationary period.","question":"Which statement about elimination periods is NOT correct?","options":["Benefits are paid retroactively to the start of the period if the insured stays disabled through it","It follows the start of each disability","It functions like a time deductible","Longer elimination periods reduce the premium"],"answer":"Benefits are paid retroactively to the start of the period if the insured stays disabled through it"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-probscenario","topic":"Probationary + Elimination Together","explanation":"Probationary periods (commonly 15 or 30 days) block SICKNESS claims early in the policy; accidents are covered immediately. After the probationary period, sickness claims still face the elimination period.","question":"A disability policy typically covers:","options":["Accidents immediately, sickness only after the probationary period","Sickness immediately, accidents after 15 days","Both only after 15 days","Both immediately, with no waiting of any kind"],"answer":"Accidents immediately, sickness only after the probationary period"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-probscenario","topic":"Probationary + Elimination Together","explanation":"Probationary periods for sickness typically run 15 or 30 days. Accidents are covered from day one.","question":"Sickness claims during a disability policy\'s probationary period are typically excluded for:","options":["15 or 30 days","Three or five days","60 or 90 days","90 or 180 days"],"answer":"15 or 30 days"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-probscenario","topic":"Probationary + Elimination Together","explanation":"COURSE KEY: in this course\'s bank, the elimination period — like the probationary period — applies to SICKNESS only and does NOT apply to accidents. Hit by a truck/train = benefits payable immediately on the date of the accident. (The book says elimination periods \'may apply only to sickness depending on the policy\' — this bank treats that as the default.)","question":"Hugo\'s policy has a 15-day probationary period and a 30-day elimination period. He is hit by a truck on September 1 (after the probationary period) and disabled for six months. Benefits first become payable:","options":["September 1 — immediately, because elimination periods do not apply to accidents","October 1 — 30 days after the accident","September 15","November 1"],"answer":"September 1 — immediately, because elimination periods do not apply to accidents"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-girdetail","topic":"Guaranteed Insurability (DI)","explanation":"The guaranteed insurability rider lets the insured buy additional coverage at predetermined intervals without new evidence of insurability; in disability policies the increase is tied to an earnings test — you can\'t insure income you don\'t earn.","question":"A guaranteed insurability rider on a disability income policy allows the insured to purchase additional coverage:","options":["Based on an earnings test, without new evidence of insurability","Based solely on inflation","Only after age 65","Whenever premiums are waived"],"answer":"Based on an earnings test, without new evidence of insurability"},{"module":"Day 4 Module 2","group":"di-girdetail","topic":"Guaranteed Insurability (DI)","explanation":"Waiver of premium applies to disability income policies (not typically medical expense policies), may apply retroactively, and usually drops off at age 60 or 65.","question":"Which statement about the waiver of premium provision is NOT correct?","options":["It normally applies to both medical expense and disability income policies","It may apply retroactively","It usually drops off at age 60 or 65","It exempts the insured from premiums during total and permanent disability"],"answer":"It normally applies to both medical expense and disability income policies"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-sums","topic":"Principal vs. Capital Sum","explanation":"Principal sum = the death benefit paid for accidental death. Capital sum = the dismemberment/loss-of-sight benefit, usually a percentage of the principal sum.","question":"The amount payable as a death benefit in an accidental death and dismemberment policy is called the:","options":["Principal sum","Capital sum","Primary amount","Indemnity amount"],"answer":"Principal sum"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-sums","topic":"Principal vs. Capital Sum","explanation":"Dismemberment or loss-of-sight benefits are the CAPITAL sum — usually a percentage of the principal (death) sum.","question":"Alexander loses one eye in an accident and receives $15,000 from his $100,000 AD&D policy. The $15,000 is the policy\'s:","options":["Capital sum","Principal sum","Secondary sum","Contingent amount"],"answer":"Capital sum"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-nature","topic":"Nature of AD&D","explanation":"AD&D is pure accident insurance and a VALUED contract. It never pays for death by sickness (heart attack); a triple-indemnity policy pays three times the principal sum for qualifying accidental deaths.","question":"Which of the following AD&D examples is ACCURATE?","options":["Laura\'s $40,000 AD&D policy pays triple indemnity; killed in a train wreck, her beneficiary receives $120,000","Merle dies of a heart attack; his $50,000 AD&D policy pays the death benefit","Karen\'s $15,000 benefit for loss of one hand is called the principal sum","Derek\'s $30,000 accidental death benefit is the policy\'s capital sum"],"answer":"Laura\'s $40,000 AD&D policy pays triple indemnity; killed in a train wreck, her beneficiary receives $120,000"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-nature","topic":"Nature of AD&D","explanation":"AD&D pays predetermined, stated amounts — making it a valued contract (a policy of value), not a contract of indemnity.","question":"An AD&D policy is best described as:","options":["A valued contract that is pure accident insurance","A contract of indemnity","A reimbursement contract","A medical expense policy"],"answer":"A valued contract that is pure accident insurance"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-forms","topic":"Limited & Special Risk","explanation":"A round-trip travel accident policy bought at the airport covers one specific named risk — a LIMITED risk policy. Special risk covers unusual hazards like a violinist\'s hands.","question":"Edith purchases a round-trip travel accident policy at the airport before a business trip. Her policy is a:","options":["Limited risk policy","Special risk policy","Business overhead expense policy","Industrial health policy"],"answer":"Limited risk policy"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-forms","topic":"Limited & Special Risk","explanation":"Special risk policies cover unusual hazards not insurable under standard AD&D — like a professional violinist insuring her hands.","question":"A professional violinist who insures her hands against loss has purchased a:","options":["Special risk policy","Limited risk policy","Dread disease policy","Franchise policy"],"answer":"Special risk policy"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-means","topic":"Means vs. Results (AD&D)","explanation":"Accidental MEANS requires both cause and result to be unintentional (jumping = no coverage). Accidental RESULTS requires only the injury to be unintentional (jumping and getting hurt = covered).","question":"Under an \'accidental means\' definition, which loss would be covered?","options":["Falling off a ladder and breaking a leg","Jumping off a ladder and breaking a leg","An intentionally self-inflicted injury","A heart attack while at rest"],"answer":"Falling off a ladder and breaking a leg"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-rules","topic":"AD&D Payment Rules","explanation":"True: dismemberment benefits MAY be paid for loss of USE, and accidental death benefits pay only if death results from accidental bodily injury as defined in the policy. False: death must typically occur within 90 days of the accident — not 60.","question":"Which statements about AD&D coverage are true? I. Death benefits are paid only if death occurs within 60 days of an accident. II. Dismemberment benefits may be paid for loss of use. III. Accidental death benefits are paid only if death results from accidental bodily injury as defined in the policy.","options":["II and III","I and II","I and III","All statements apply"],"answer":"II and III"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-rules","topic":"AD&D Payment Rules","explanation":"Per the course bank: losing all fingers EXCEPT the thumb is NOT dismemberment (severance must be of the entire hand), but permanent LOSS OF USE of a hand/arm DOES qualify.","question":"Which would qualify as dismemberment? I. Sally loses all fingers on her left hand except the thumb. II. Ed permanently loses the USE of his right hand and arm in an auto accident.","options":["II only","I only","I and II","Neither I nor II"],"answer":"II only"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-sums","topic":"Principal vs. Capital Sum","explanation":"COURSE KEY: the principal sum pays for LOSS OF LIFE ONLY. Loss of hands, partial foot, or fingers — even severe multiple losses — were keyed to the CAPITAL sum, not principal. (Note the bank is loose here: another of its questions says loss of two limbs pays the same amount as death — but when asked what the principal sum \'pays for,\' answer death only.)","question":"[Course bank] The principal sum in a $25,000 AD&D policy will pay for which of the following? I. Loss of hands above the wrist. II. Loss of 3/4 of the foot. III. Loss of life in a boating accident. IV. All fingers (including thumbs) on both hands.","options":["III only","I and III","I, II, and III","II and IV"],"answer":"III only"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 1","group":"add-sums","topic":"Principal vs. Capital Sum","explanation":"COURSE KEY: the capital sum covers the dismemberment losses — this bank keyed ALL the listed dismemberments (hands above the wrist, partial foot, an eye, all fingers including thumbs) as payable under the capital sum schedule (at varying percentages). Death is the only loss paid by the principal sum.","question":"[Course bank] The capital sum in an AD&D policy will pay for which of the following? I. Loss of hands above the wrist. II. Loss of 3/4 of the foot. III. Loss of an eye. IV. All fingers (including thumbs) on both hands.","options":["I, II, III, and IV","I and III","II and IV","I, II, and III"],"answer":"I, II, III, and IV"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-parts","topic":"Parts of Medicare","explanation":"Part A = hospital (premium-free with 40 work quarters). Part B = doctors/outpatient, 80/20 after deductible, monthly premium. Part C = Advantage (requires A+B). Part D = drugs.","question":"Inpatient hospital care is covered under which part of Medicare?","options":["Part A","Part B","Part C","Part D"],"answer":"Part A"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-parts","topic":"Parts of Medicare","explanation":"Part A = hospital (premium-free with 40 work quarters). Part B = doctors/outpatient, 80/20 after deductible, monthly premium. Part C = Advantage (requires A+B). Part D = drugs.","question":"After the annual deductible, Medicare Part B generally pays what share of approved charges?","options":["80%","100%","50%","20%"],"answer":"80%"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-partc","topic":"Medicare Advantage","explanation":"Part C (Medicare Advantage) plans are private plans that replace original Medicare; enrollees must be enrolled in BOTH Part A and Part B.","question":"To enroll in a Medicare Advantage (Part C) plan, a person must:","options":["Be enrolled in both Part A and Part B","Be enrolled in Part D only","Have a Medigap policy","Be under age 65"],"answer":"Be enrolled in both Part A and Part B"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-partc","topic":"Medicare Advantage","explanation":"Part C (Medicare Advantage) plans are private plans that replace original Medicare; enrollees must be enrolled in BOTH Part A and Part B.","question":"Prescription drug coverage under Medicare is provided by:","options":["Part D plans offered by private companies","Part A automatically","Part B with no premium","Medigap Plan A"],"answer":"Part D plans offered by private companies"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-parta","topic":"Medicare Part A","explanation":"Part A is compulsory hospital insurance financed by FICA taxes, and it is provided AUTOMATICALLY when a qualified person applies for Social Security benefits.","question":"Choose the CORRECT statement pertaining to Medicare.","options":["When a qualified individual applies for Social Security benefits, Medicare Part A is automatically provided","Individuals enrolled in Part A are allowed one 90-day benefit period annually","Medicare Part B pays 80% of the deductible","Part A is financed by monthly premiums"],"answer":"When a qualified individual applies for Social Security benefits, Medicare Part A is automatically provided"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-parta","topic":"Medicare Part A","explanation":"For the first 60 days of hospitalization, Part A covers all eligible services except the initial deductible. Past 90 days, the patient draws on a 60-day lifetime reserve.","question":"Except for an initial deductible, Medicare Part A pays 100% of covered services for the first ____ days of hospitalization.","options":["60","30","90","100"],"answer":"60"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-parta","topic":"Medicare Part A","explanation":"When hospitalization exceeds 90 days, patients tap a LIFETIME RESERVE of 60 additional hospital days — once used, they never renew.","question":"After 90 days of hospitalization in one benefit period, a Medicare patient draws on:","options":["A lifetime reserve of 60 hospital days","A new annual benefit period","Unlimited extended coverage","Medicaid automatically"],"answer":"A lifetime reserve of 60 hospital days"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-parta","topic":"Medicare Part A","explanation":"Medicare pays up to 100 days of skilled nursing facility care per benefit period (following a qualifying hospital stay).","question":"Medicare will pay for how many days of skilled nursing facility care?","options":["100","30","60","90"],"answer":"100"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-partb","topic":"Medicare Part B","explanation":"Part B participants pay a monthly premium, an annual deductible, and 20% of covered charges. There is NO per-benefit deductible.","question":"Under Medicare Part B, which of the following do participants NOT have to pay?","options":["A per-benefit deductible","An annual deductible","20% of covered charges above the deductible","A monthly premium"],"answer":"A per-benefit deductible"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-partb","topic":"Medicare Part B","explanation":"Part B is VOLUNTARY — not compulsory. It covers what Part A doesn\'t (doctors, outpatient) and is financed by monthly premiums plus general tax revenues.","question":"Choose the INCORRECT statement regarding Medicare Part B.","options":["Medicare Part B is a compulsory program","Part B covers services and supplies not covered by Part A","Part B is financed by monthly premiums","Part B is financed in part by tax revenues"],"answer":"Medicare Part B is a compulsory program"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-payor","topic":"Primary vs. Secondary Payor","explanation":"A working person 65+ at an employer with 20 or more employees keeps the employer-sponsored plan as PRIMARY coverage; Medicare is SECONDARY.","question":"Joan, 67, still works for a firm with 75 employees and has the company health plan. Which is true?","options":["The employer plan is primary; Medicare is secondary","Medicare is primary; the employer plan is secondary","She must drop the employer plan at 65","She cannot have both coverages"],"answer":"The employer plan is primary; Medicare is secondary"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-exclusions","topic":"Medicare Exclusions","explanation":"Medicare excludes: private duty nursing, private rooms (unless medically necessary), first 3 pints of blood, skilled nursing past 100 days, charges above Medicare-approved amounts, care outside the U.S., custodial care at home, and well care (dental, vision, hearing, routine physicals, immunizations, acupuncture).","question":"Which of the following IS excluded under Medicare?","options":["The first three pints of blood","Inpatient hospital care","Hospice care","Home health care"],"answer":"The first three pints of blood"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-medicaid2","topic":"Medicaid & Florida Programs","explanation":"Unlike Medicare, Medicaid DOES cover custodial/assisted nursing-home care — for people of any age who can demonstrate financial need.","question":"Which program covers custodial care in a nursing home for a person who can demonstrate financial need?","options":["Medicaid","Medicare Part A","Medicare Part B","Workers\' compensation"],"answer":"Medicaid"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-medicaid2","topic":"Medicaid & Florida Programs","explanation":"Florida penalizes asset transfers below market value made to qualify for Medicaid: eligibility can be delayed for transfers within the 5-year look-back period.","question":"Transferring assets below market value to qualify for Medicaid can delay eligibility if done within the look-back period of:","options":["5 years","1 year","3 years","10 years"],"answer":"5 years"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-medicaid2","topic":"Medicaid & Florida Programs","explanation":"The Deficit Reduction Act (DRA) let states modernize Medicaid through cost sharing, flexible benefits, and healthy opportunity accounts. Florida Healthy Kids Corporation (1990) expands children\'s coverage.","question":"The Florida Healthy Kids Corporation, established in 1990, was created to:","options":["Enhance access to health insurance for uninsured children","Replace Medicaid for seniors","Provide workers\' compensation to minors","Sell Medicare Advantage plans"],"answer":"Enhance access to health insurance for uninsured children"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-wc","topic":"Workers\' Compensation","explanation":"Workers\' comp is NO-FAULT — benefits are paid regardless of who caused the work-related injury. It exists in all 50 states, pays health-care costs and disability income, and aims to return workers to work.","question":"Choose the statement concerning workers\' compensation that is NOT correct.","options":["Workers receive benefits only if they are not at fault for their work-related injury","One purpose of workers\' compensation laws is to return injured persons to work","Benefits include healthcare costs and disability income","All 50 states have workers\' compensation laws"],"answer":"Workers receive benefits only if they are not at fault for their work-related injury"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 2","group":"mc-wc","topic":"Workers\' Compensation","explanation":"Employers can meet their WC obligation through a state program, a private insurer, or self-insurance.","question":"Employers may provide workers\' compensation coverage through all of the following EXCEPT:","options":["Deducting premiums from employee paychecks","A state program","A private insurer","Self-insurance"],"answer":"Deducting premiums from employee paychecks"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-medigap","topic":"Medigap Open Enrollment","explanation":"Medigap plans are standardized by letter. The 6-month open enrollment starts when a person is 65+ AND enrolled in Part B — guaranteed issue, no underwriting. Florida allows a 30-day free look.","question":"Ruth turned 65 and enrolled in Part B this month. Her guaranteed-issue window to buy any Medigap policy lasts:","options":["6 months","30 days","12 months","Until age 70"],"answer":"6 months"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-medigap","topic":"Medigap Open Enrollment","explanation":"Medigap plans are standardized by letter. The 6-month open enrollment starts when a person is 65+ AND enrolled in Part B — guaranteed issue, no underwriting. Florida allows a 30-day free look.","question":"Which statement about Medicare supplement (Medigap) plans is TRUE?","options":["Benefits for a given lettered plan are identical no matter which insurer sells it","Each insurer designs its own unique benefits","They replace Medicare entirely","They include long-term custodial care"],"answer":"Benefits for a given lettered plan are identical no matter which insurer sells it"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-ltctrigger","topic":"LTC Benefit Triggers","explanation":"LTC benefits trigger on inability to perform 2 of 6 ADLs (bathing, dressing, eating, transferring, toileting, continence) or cognitive impairment.","question":"Long-term care policy benefits are typically triggered when the insured cannot perform:","options":["Two of six activities of daily living, or has cognitive impairment","Any one household chore","All six activities of daily living","Gainful employment of any kind"],"answer":"Two of six activities of daily living, or has cognitive impairment"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-ltctrigger","topic":"LTC Benefit Triggers","explanation":"LTC benefits trigger on inability to perform 2 of 6 ADLs (bathing, dressing, eating, transferring, toileting, continence) or cognitive impairment.","question":"Which of the following is an activity of daily living (ADL) used in LTC benefit triggers?","options":["Bathing","Driving","Cooking","Managing finances"],"answer":"Bathing"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-ltccare","topic":"Levels of LTC Care","explanation":"Skilled = daily medical care by professionals; intermediate = occasional skilled care; custodial = help with daily living, the most common need — and NOT covered by Medicare.","question":"Help with bathing, dressing, and eating provided by aides without medical training is called:","options":["Custodial care","Skilled nursing care","Intermediate care","Acute care"],"answer":"Custodial care"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-ltccare","topic":"Levels of LTC Care","explanation":"Skilled = daily medical care by professionals; intermediate = occasional skilled care; custodial = help with daily living, the most common need — and NOT covered by Medicare.","question":"Which statement about Medicare and long-term care is TRUE?","options":["Medicare does NOT cover custodial care — the most common long-term care need","Medicare covers unlimited nursing home stays","Medicare Part D covers custodial care","Medicare covers custodial care after a 3-day hospital stay"],"answer":"Medicare does NOT cover custodial care — the most common long-term care need"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-partner","topic":"Florida LTC Partnership","explanation":"Florida\'s LTC Partnership lets buyers of qualifying policies protect assets equal to benefits paid when later applying for Medicaid. LTC policies must be at least guaranteed renewable; FL free look is 30 days.","question":"Esme\'s Florida Partnership LTC policy paid $200,000 in benefits before she applied for Medicaid. The Partnership program lets her:","options":["Protect $200,000 of assets from Medicaid spend-down requirements","Skip Medicaid\'s income test entirely","Transfer all assets to her children penalty-free","Double her Medicaid benefits"],"answer":"Protect $200,000 of assets from Medicaid spend-down requirements"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-partner","topic":"Florida LTC Partnership","explanation":"Florida\'s LTC Partnership lets buyers of qualifying policies protect assets equal to benefits paid when later applying for Medicaid. LTC policies must be at least guaranteed renewable; FL free look is 30 days.","question":"Long-term care policies sold in Florida must be at least:","options":["Guaranteed renewable","Cancellable","Optionally renewable","Annually re-underwritten"],"answer":"Guaranteed renewable"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mg-core","topic":"Medigap Basics","explanation":"The NAIC core policy (Plan A) covers Part A coinsurance, the first 3 pints of blood yearly, and the 20% Part B coinsurance — it does NOT cover the Part A deductible.","question":"Which of the following is NOT part of the core (Plan A) standard Medicare supplement policy?","options":["The Medicare Part A deductible","Coinsurance amounts of Medicare Part A","The first three pints of blood each year","The 20% coinsurance for Medicare-approved Part B services"],"answer":"The Medicare Part A deductible"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mg-core","topic":"Medigap Basics","explanation":"Medigap fills the gaps in Medicare Parts A and B. A Medicare Advantage enrollee doesn\'t need one — and selling an MA plan to a Medigap owner is ILLEGAL because it duplicates coverage.","question":"Selling a Medicare Advantage plan to someone who already owns a Medigap policy is:","options":["Illegal, because it duplicates coverage","Encouraged, for extra protection","Allowed with a signed waiver","Required by the ACA"],"answer":"Illegal, because it duplicates coverage"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"ltc-def","topic":"LTC Fundamentals","explanation":"LTC serves people who lost full independence, with care typically extending beyond 90 days; the policy pays a SET daily benefit regardless of actual expenses.","question":"Long-term care insurance pays benefits on what basis?","options":["A set dollar amount per day of care, regardless of actual expenses","Reimbursement of all actual expenses","A percentage of the insured\'s income","Whatever Medicare doesn\'t pay"],"answer":"A set dollar amount per day of care, regardless of actual expenses"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"ltc-def","topic":"LTC Fundamentals","explanation":"A chronic illness can be managed but not cured (diabetes, heart disease, asthma); an acute illness can be fully recovered from with care (pneumonia).","question":"A medical condition requiring ongoing care and management, such as diabetes or heart disease, is a(n):","options":["Chronic illness","Acute illness","Sudden illness","Prolonged illness"],"answer":"Chronic illness"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"ltc-levels","topic":"Levels of LTC Care","explanation":"Skilled nursing care must be available round-the-clock (24 hours); intermediate care is provided periodically under physician supervision, not continuously.","question":"How does skilled nursing care differ from intermediate care?","options":["Skilled care is continuous 24-hour care; intermediate care is periodic","Skilled care requires no medical training","Intermediate care is only given in hospitals","Skilled care only covers bathing and dressing"],"answer":"Skilled care is continuous 24-hour care; intermediate care is periodic"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"ltc-levels","topic":"Levels of LTC Care","explanation":"Respite care provides short-term relief for FAMILY CAREGIVERS. Adult day care supports people during the day; home health care is delivered in the home.","question":"Short-term care designed to give relief to a family member who normally cares for the insured is called:","options":["Respite care","Custodial care","Continuing care","Alternative care"],"answer":"Respite care"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"ltc-prov","topic":"LTC Provisions & Limits","explanation":"LTC exclusions typically include drug and alcohol dependence, self-inflicted injuries, acts of war, and nonorganic mental illness. Alzheimer\'s, dementia, and Parkinson\'s ARE covered.","question":"Which condition is generally NOT covered by a long-term care policy?","options":["Alcohol dependency","Alzheimer\'s disease","Senile dementia","Parkinson\'s disease"],"answer":"Alcohol dependency"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"ltc-prov","topic":"LTC Provisions & Limits","explanation":"Premiums depend on age and health, benefit type/level, the presence and length of an elimination period, AND riders/options — not solely on age, health, and benefit type. Policies must be guaranteed renewable; benefit periods typically run 2–6 years.","question":"Which statement about long-term care policies is NOT correct?","options":["Premiums are based solely on the insured\'s age, health, and type of benefit","Maximum coverage periods typically extend from two to six years","LTC policies must be guaranteed renewable","Longer elimination periods generally mean lower premiums"],"answer":"Premiums are based solely on the insured\'s age, health, and type of benefit"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"ltc-group","topic":"Group LTC & Taxation","explanation":"Group LTC advantages: no individual underwriting and coverage for multiple family members. LTC benefits received are excluded from income for tax purposes.","question":"Benefits received from a long-term care policy are:","options":["Excluded from income for tax purposes","Taxed as ordinary income","Taxed at capital gains rates","Taxable above $10,000 per year"],"answer":"Excluded from income for tax purposes"},{"module":"Day 5 Module 3","group":"mc-partner","topic":"Florida LTC Partnership","explanation":"The State Partnership Program is a partnership among the STATES, the INSURANCE INDUSTRY, and INSUREDS — allowing Medicaid reimbursement without impoverishment. The insurance commissioner is not a party to the partnership.","question":"The State Partnership Program for Long-Term Care includes all of the following EXCEPT:","options":["The insurance commissioner","The states","The insurance industry","Insureds"],"answer":"The insurance commissioner"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-grace","topic":"Grace Periods","explanation":"Florida grace periods follow the premium mode: 7 days (weekly), 10 days (monthly), 31 days (all other modes). Coverage continues during the grace period.","question":"Tessa pays her health insurance premium monthly. If she misses a payment, how long is her grace period?","options":["10 days","7 days","31 days","45 days"],"answer":"10 days"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-grace","topic":"Grace Periods","explanation":"Florida grace periods follow the premium mode: 7 days (weekly), 10 days (monthly), 31 days (all other modes). Coverage continues during the grace period.","question":"A health policy with premiums paid quarterly has a grace period of:","options":["31 days","10 days","7 days","60 days"],"answer":"31 days"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-reinstate","topic":"Reinstatement","explanation":"If the insurer requires a reinstatement application and gives a conditional receipt, the policy reinstates automatically on the 45th day unless disapproved in writing. A reinstated policy covers accidents immediately but sickness only after 10 days.","question":"Omar applied to reinstate his lapsed health policy and received a conditional receipt. The insurer never responded. His policy is automatically reinstated after:","options":["45 days","10 days","31 days","90 days"],"answer":"45 days"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-reinstate","topic":"Reinstatement","explanation":"If the insurer requires a reinstatement application and gives a conditional receipt, the policy reinstates automatically on the 45th day unless disapproved in writing. A reinstated policy covers accidents immediately but sickness only after 10 days.","question":"Three days after his policy was reinstated, Felix came down with pneumonia. Five days after reinstatement, he broke his wrist. What does the reinstated policy cover?","options":["The broken wrist, but not the pneumonia — sickness is covered only after 10 days","Both losses in full","Neither loss for 31 days","The pneumonia, but not the wrist"],"answer":"The broken wrist, but not the pneumonia — sickness is covered only after 10 days"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-claims","topic":"The Claims Clock","explanation":"Claims deadlines in order: notice of claim 20 days → insurer sends forms within 15 days → proof of loss within 90 days → payment immediately (DI at least monthly) → legal action no sooner than 60 days, up to 5 years in Florida.","question":"After a loss, the insured must give the insurer notice of claim within:","options":["20 days","15 days","90 days","60 days"],"answer":"20 days"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-claims","topic":"The Claims Clock","explanation":"Claims deadlines in order: notice of claim 20 days → insurer sends forms within 15 days → proof of loss within 90 days → payment immediately (DI at least monthly) → legal action no sooner than 60 days, up to 5 years in Florida.","question":"If the insurer fails to send claim forms within 15 days of notice, the insured:","options":["May submit proof of loss in any written form","Loses the right to claim","Must wait 90 days and renotify","Automatically wins the claim"],"answer":"May submit proof of loss in any written form"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-proof","topic":"Proof of Loss","explanation":"Proof of loss is due within 90 days of the loss; legal action must wait at least 60 days after proof and, in Florida, may be brought up to 5 years.","question":"Written proof of loss must generally be furnished to the insurer within:","options":["90 days of the loss","20 days of the loss","15 days of the loss","12 months of the loss"],"answer":"90 days of the loss"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-proof","topic":"Proof of Loss","explanation":"Proof of loss is due within 90 days of the loss; legal action must wait at least 60 days after proof and, in Florida, may be brought up to 5 years.","question":"How long after submitting proof of loss must an insured wait before filing a lawsuit against the insurer?","options":["60 days","20 days","90 days","5 years"],"answer":"60 days"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-defenses","topic":"Incontestability","explanation":"After 2 years, the insurer cannot void the policy or deny claims based on application misstatements — except fraudulent ones. Misstated age just adjusts the benefit.","question":"Under the time limit on certain defenses provision, an insurer cannot deny a claim due to misstatements on the application after:","options":["2 years, unless the misstatement was fraudulent","1 year, without exception","5 years, unless premiums lapsed","6 months, unless sickness-related"],"answer":"2 years, unless the misstatement was fraudulent"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-defenses","topic":"Incontestability","explanation":"After 2 years, the insurer cannot void the policy or deny claims based on application misstatements — except fraudulent ones. Misstated age just adjusts the benefit.","question":"The insurer discovers the insured understated her age on the application. Under the misstatement of age provision, the insurer will:","options":["Adjust benefits to what the premium would have purchased at her true age","Void the policy retroactively","Deny all pending claims","Cancel the policy with 45 days notice"],"answer":"Adjust benefits to what the premium would have purchased at her true age"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-freelook","topic":"Free Look Periods","explanation":"Florida health policies carry a 10-day free look; Medicare supplement and long-term care policies carry 30 days. The clock starts at delivery.","question":"In Florida, the free look period for a standard individual health policy and for a Medicare supplement policy are, respectively:","options":["10 days and 30 days","30 days and 10 days","10 days and 10 days","31 days and 45 days"],"answer":"10 days and 30 days"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-freelook","topic":"Free Look Periods","explanation":"Florida health policies carry a 10-day free look; Medicare supplement and long-term care policies carry 30 days. The clock starts at delivery.","question":"Nadia\'s long-term care policy was delivered on March 1. How long does she have to return it for a full refund?","options":["30 days from delivery","10 days from delivery","45 days from issue","No return is permitted"],"answer":"30 days from delivery"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-entire","topic":"Entire Contract","explanation":"The policy plus attached application form the entire contract. Only an executive officer of the insurer — never the agent — may modify it.","question":"Who has the authority to modify the terms of an issued health insurance policy?","options":["An executive officer of the insurer","The selling agent","The policyowner\'s attorney","Any licensed adjuster"],"answer":"An executive officer of the insurer"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-entire","topic":"Entire Contract","explanation":"The policy plus attached application form the entire contract. Only an executive officer of the insurer — never the agent — may modify it.","question":"The entire contract provision states that the contract consists of:","options":["The policy and the attached application","The policy, the agent\'s notes, and any verbal promises","The application alone","The policy and the insurer\'s underwriting file"],"answer":"The policy and the attached application"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-riders","topic":"Exclusion Riders","explanation":"An impairment (exclusion) rider removes a named preexisting condition from coverage, letting an otherwise uninsurable applicant obtain a policy.","question":"Dimitri has a chronic knee condition. The insurer offers him a policy that covers everything EXCEPT that knee. This is accomplished through:","options":["An impairment (exclusion) rider","A guaranteed insurability rider","A waiver of premium rider","A cost-of-living rider"],"answer":"An impairment (exclusion) rider"},{"module":"Next: Policy Provisions","group":"pp-riders","topic":"Exclusion Riders","explanation":"An impairment (exclusion) rider removes a named preexisting condition from coverage, letting an otherwise uninsurable applicant obtain a policy.","question":"The rider that allows an insured to purchase additional coverage later without evidence of insurability is the:","options":["Guaranteed insurability rider","Impairment rider","Multiple indemnity rider","Probationary rider"],"answer":"Guaranteed insurability rider"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-group","topic":"Group Plan Mechanics","explanation":"Group insurance: the employer holds the master contract, employees get certificates, and eligible employees who enroll on time face no individual underwriting.","question":"In a group health plan, individual employees receive:","options":["Certificates of insurance under the employer\'s master contract","Their own individual policies","Copies of the master contract to sign","Conditional receipts"],"answer":"Certificates of insurance under the employer\'s master contract"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-group","topic":"Group Plan Mechanics","explanation":"Group insurance: the employer holds the master contract, employees get certificates, and eligible employees who enroll on time face no individual underwriting.","question":"An eligible employee who enrolls in the group plan during the enrollment period:","options":["Cannot be required to prove individual insurability","Must pass a physical exam","Must provide an attending physician statement","Is underwritten individually like any applicant"],"answer":"Cannot be required to prove individual insurability"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-cobra","topic":"COBRA Durations","explanation":"COBRA (employers with 20+ employees): 18 months for termination/reduced hours, 29 months if disabled, 36 months for dependent events (death, divorce, Medicare entitlement, child aging out). Premium may be up to 102%.","question":"Priscilla quit her job at a 200-employee firm. Under COBRA she may continue her group coverage for up to:","options":["18 months","29 months","36 months","12 months"],"answer":"18 months"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-cobra","topic":"COBRA Durations","explanation":"COBRA (employers with 20+ employees): 18 months for termination/reduced hours, 29 months if disabled, 36 months for dependent events (death, divorce, Medicare entitlement, child aging out). Premium may be up to 102%.","question":"After her divorce from a covered employee, Renata may continue group coverage under COBRA for up to:","options":["36 months","18 months","29 months","60 months"],"answer":"36 months"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-cobra102","topic":"COBRA Premium","explanation":"COBRA continuants pay their own premium, which may be up to 102% of the group rate — the extra 2% covers administration.","question":"A COBRA continuant may be charged up to what percentage of the group premium?","options":["102%","100%","150%","115%"],"answer":"102%"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-cobra102","topic":"COBRA Premium","explanation":"COBRA continuants pay their own premium, which may be up to 102% of the group rate — the extra 2% covers administration.","question":"Under COBRA, the cost of continued coverage is paid by:","options":["The former employee or beneficiary, at up to 102% of the group rate","The employer, as a severance benefit","The state continuation fund","Medicare"],"answer":"The former employee or beneficiary, at up to 102% of the group rate"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-flcont","topic":"Florida Continuation","explanation":"Florida\'s Health Insurance Coverage Continuation Act (§627.6692) gives employees of small employers (under 20 employees) continuation rights — generally 18 months — where federal COBRA doesn\'t apply.","question":"Jonas works for a 12-person company in Florida and loses his job. His group continuation rights come from:","options":["Florida\'s Health Insurance Coverage Continuation Act — federal COBRA doesn\'t apply to employers under 20","Federal COBRA","ERISA preemption","The ACA employer mandate"],"answer":"Florida\'s Health Insurance Coverage Continuation Act — federal COBRA doesn\'t apply to employers under 20"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-flcont","topic":"Florida Continuation","explanation":"Florida\'s Health Insurance Coverage Continuation Act (§627.6692) gives employees of small employers (under 20 employees) continuation rights — generally 18 months — where federal COBRA doesn\'t apply.","question":"Federal COBRA applies to employers with at least how many employees?","options":["20","2","50","100"],"answer":"20"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-cob","topic":"Coordination of Benefits","explanation":"COB prevents collecting more than 100% across two plans. The employee\'s own plan is primary; for dependent children, the birthday rule makes the plan of the parent with the earlier birthday in the calendar year primary.","question":"Both of Mia\'s parents cover her under their group plans. Dad\'s birthday is March 3; Mom\'s is January 28 (Dad is older). Which plan is primary for Mia?","options":["Mom\'s — her birthday falls earlier in the calendar year","Dad\'s — he is older","Whichever plan has higher benefits","Both pay 50% each"],"answer":"Mom\'s — her birthday falls earlier in the calendar year"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-cob","topic":"Coordination of Benefits","explanation":"COB prevents collecting more than 100% across two plans. The employee\'s own plan is primary; for dependent children, the birthday rule makes the plan of the parent with the earlier birthday in the calendar year primary.","question":"The purpose of the coordination of benefits provision is to:","options":["Prevent the insured from collecting more than 100% of a claim across multiple plans","Increase total benefits for two-income families","Let insurers split commissions","Guarantee dual coverage for dependents"],"answer":"Prevent the insured from collecting more than 100% of a claim across multiple plans"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-convert","topic":"Conversion Privilege","explanation":"An employee leaving a group has 31 days to convert to an individual policy without proving insurability — at individual (higher) rates.","question":"After leaving the group, an employee may convert to an individual policy without evidence of insurability within:","options":["31 days","10 days","60 days","6 months"],"answer":"31 days"},{"module":"Next: Group Health & COBRA","group":"gh-convert","topic":"Conversion Privilege","explanation":"An employee leaving a group has 31 days to convert to an individual policy without proving insurability — at individual (higher) rates.","question":"Which statement about group conversion is TRUE?","options":["No proof of insurability is required, but the individual premium will be higher than the group rate","The group rate is locked in for life","A physical exam is always required","Conversion is available only to disabled employees"],"answer":"No proof of insurability is required, but the individual premium will be higher than the group rate"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-dfs-oir","topic":"DFS vs. OIR","explanation":"DFS (headed by the elected CFO) licenses and disciplines agents. OIR regulates insurers — certificates of authority, forms, rates, financial exams.","question":"Which Florida body licenses and disciplines insurance AGENTS?","options":["The Department of Financial Services (DFS)","The Office of Insurance Regulation (OIR)","The NAIC","The Florida Supreme Court"],"answer":"The Department of Financial Services (DFS)"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-dfs-oir","topic":"DFS vs. OIR","explanation":"DFS (headed by the elected CFO) licenses and disciplines agents. OIR regulates insurers — certificates of authority, forms, rates, financial exams.","question":"Approving policy forms and issuing certificates of authority to insurers in Florida is the job of:","options":["The Office of Insurance Regulation (OIR)","The Department of Financial Services (DFS)","The state legislature","The State Guaranty Association"],"answer":"The Office of Insurance Regulation (OIR)"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-license","topic":"2-40 License Requirements","explanation":"2-40 applicants must be 18+, Florida residents, fingerprinted, complete a 40-hour approved prelicensing course, and pass the state exam.","question":"The prelicensing education requirement for a Florida 2-40 health agent license is:","options":["40 hours","24 hours","60 hours","200 hours"],"answer":"40 hours"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-license","topic":"2-40 License Requirements","explanation":"2-40 applicants must be 18+, Florida residents, fingerprinted, complete a 40-hour approved prelicensing course, and pass the state exam.","question":"Which of the following is NOT required to obtain a Florida 2-40 license?","options":["A four-year college degree","Being at least 18 years old","Fingerprints for a background check","Passing the state examination"],"answer":"A four-year college degree"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-ce","topic":"Continuing Education","explanation":"Florida CE: 24 hours every 2 years (20 hours once licensed 6+ years), including a required law-and-ethics update course.","question":"An agent licensed in Florida for 3 years must complete how much continuing education?","options":["24 hours every 2 years","20 hours every 2 years","40 hours every year","No CE until year 6"],"answer":"24 hours every 2 years"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-ce","topic":"Continuing Education","explanation":"Florida CE: 24 hours every 2 years (20 hours once licensed 6+ years), including a required law-and-ethics update course.","question":"After an agent has been licensed for 6 or more years, the Florida CE requirement drops to:","options":["20 hours every 2 years","24 hours every 2 years","10 hours every year","Zero — CE is waived"],"answer":"20 hours every 2 years"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-fiduciary","topic":"Fiduciary Duty","explanation":"Premiums collected are trust funds held in a fiduciary capacity — they belong to the insurer or insured, never the agent. Misuse is misappropriation, a criminal offense.","question":"Premiums an agent collects from clients are legally:","options":["Trust funds held in a fiduciary capacity","The agent\'s income until remitted","A loan from the insurer","Commission advances"],"answer":"Trust funds held in a fiduciary capacity"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-fiduciary","topic":"Fiduciary Duty","explanation":"Premiums collected are trust funds held in a fiduciary capacity — they belong to the insurer or insured, never the agent. Misuse is misappropriation, a criminal offense.","question":"An agent who deposits client premiums into his personal account and uses them to pay rent has committed:","options":["Misappropriation of fiduciary funds","Rebating","Twisting","Defamation"],"answer":"Misappropriation of fiduciary funds"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-sliding","topic":"Sliding","explanation":"Sliding is charging for or attaching products the buyer didn\'t agree to — e.g., automatically adding an ancillary product to every sale.","question":"An agent adds a $10-per-month accidental death rider to every health policy she sells without telling the clients. This practice is:","options":["Sliding","Twisting","Churning","Coercion"],"answer":"Sliding"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-sliding","topic":"Sliding","explanation":"Sliding is charging for or attaching products the buyer didn\'t agree to — e.g., automatically adding an ancillary product to every sale.","question":"Which best defines sliding?","options":["Charging an applicant for additional coverage the applicant did not agree to purchase","Replacing policies between insurers through misrepresentation","Returning part of a commission to the buyer","Making false statements about a competitor"],"answer":"Charging an applicant for additional coverage the applicant did not agree to purchase"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-fraud","topic":"Insurance Fraud","explanation":"Knowingly false statements on applications or claims constitute insurance fraud — a felony in Florida.","question":"In Florida, knowingly presenting false information on an insurance claim is:","options":["A felony","A civil infraction only","Legal if under $1,000","Grounds for CE penalties only"],"answer":"A felony"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-fraud","topic":"Insurance Fraud","explanation":"Knowingly false statements on applications or claims constitute insurance fraud — a felony in Florida.","question":"Transacting insurance in Florida without a license and appointment is:","options":["A criminal offense","Permitted for the first 6 months","Allowed if supervised by a broker","A civil matter between the parties"],"answer":"A criminal offense"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-appoint","topic":"Appointments","explanation":"An agent cannot transact insurance until appointed by an insurer; appointments renew every 24 months, and a license terminates after 48 months (4 years) without any appointment.","question":"Before transacting insurance for an insurer, a licensed Florida agent must also:","options":["Be appointed by that insurer","Register with the NAIC","Post a surety bond","Pass a second state exam"],"answer":"Be appointed by that insurer"},{"module":"Next: Florida Law & Licensing","group":"fl-appoint","topic":"Appointments","explanation":"An agent cannot transact insurance until appointed by an insurer; appointments renew every 24 months, and a license terminates after 48 months (4 years) without any appointment.","question":"Insurer appointments in Florida are renewed every:","options":["24 months","12 months","48 months","6 months"],"answer":"24 months"}]')}]);